# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alaska-native-claims-settlement-act
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Both the mushers and their dogs were portrayed as heroes in the newly popular medium of radio and received headline coverage in newspapers across the United States.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto, the lead sled dog on the final stretch into Nome, became the most famous canine celebrity of the era after Rin Tin Tin, and his statue is a popular tourist attraction in both New York City's Central Park and downtown Anchorage, Alaska.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo's team covered much of the most dangerous parts of the route and ran the farthest: Togo's team covered 261 miles (420 km) while Balto's team ran 55 miles (89 km).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] From November to July, the port on the southern shore of the Seward Peninsula of the Bering Sea was icebound and inaccessible by steamship.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The only link to the rest of the world during the winter was the Iditarod Trail, which ran 938 miles (1,510 km) from the port of Seward in the south, across several mountain ranges and the vast Alaska Interior, to the town of Nome.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In Alaska and other subarctic regions, the primary source of mail and needed supplies in 1925 was the dog sled.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Within a decade, bush flying became the dominant method of transportation during the winter months.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In the winter of 1924–1925, Curtis Welch was the only doctor in Nome.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He and four nurses, working at the small Maynard Columbus Hospital, served the town and the surrounding area.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After discovering the hospital's entire batch of diphtheria antitoxin had expired, Welch placed an order for more.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] However, the replacement shipment did not arrive before the port was closed by ice for the winter, and more could not be shipped in to Nome until spring.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In the next few weeks, after the number of cases grew and four children were dead—whom Welch had not been able to autopsy—he became increasingly concerned about diphtheria.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] By mid-January 1925, Welch officially diagnosed the first case of diphtheria in a three-year-old boy who died only two weeks after first becoming ill.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The following day, when a seven-year-old girl presented the same symptoms of diphtheria, Welch attempted to administer some of the expired antitoxin to see if it might still have any effect, but the girl died a few hours later.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Realizing that an epidemic was imminent, Welch called Nome's mayor, George Maynard, that same evening to arrange an emergency town council meeting.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The council immediately implemented a quarantine.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The following day, on January 22, 1925, Welch sent radio telegrams to all other major towns in Alaska alerting them of the public health risk.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also requested assistance from the U.S.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite the quarantine, there were over 20 confirmed cases of diphtheria and at least 50 more at risk by the end of January.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Without antitoxin, it was expected that in the surrounding region's population of around 10,000 people, the mortality rate could be close to 100 percent.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A previous influenza pandemic had hit the area in 1918, causing fatalities in about 50 percent of the native population of Nome and 8% of the native population of Alaska.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] More than 1,000 people died in northwest Alaska, and approximately 2,000 across the state.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The majority were Alaska Natives who did not have any resistance to either disease.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] At the January 24 meeting of the board of health, superintendent Mark Summers of the Hammon Consolidated Gold Fields proposed a dogsled relay using two fast teams.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] One would start at Nenana, Alaska, the closest railhead on the Alaska Railroad, and the other at Nome, and they would meet roughly halfway in the town of Nulato.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The trip from Nulato to Nome normally took 30 days.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Curtis Welch estimated that the serum would last only six days under the brutal conditions of the trail.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Summers's employee, the Norwegian sled dog trainer and musher Leonhard Seppala, was chosen for the 630-mile (1,014 km) round trip from Nome to Nulato and back.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He had previously made the run in a record-breaking four days, won the All-Alaska Sweepstakes three times, and had become famous for his athletic ability and rapport with his Siberian huskies.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] His lead dog, the 12-year-old Togo, was equally famous for his leadership, intelligence, and ability to sense danger.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Maynard proposed flying the antitoxin by plane.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1925, planes were a relatively new technology, and Alaska's harsh winter weather made them unreliable.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Several test flights had been conducted the previous year between Fairbanks and McGrath, Alaska, to determine how well a reliable aircraft could handle the winter conditions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The longest test flight flew a distance of only 260 miles (420 km), a little under half the necessary distance between Nenana and Nome.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The only planes operating in Alaska in 1925 were three vintage biplanes, which had been dismantled for the winter.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Their open cockpits and water-cooled engines would make these planes unfit for the trip as well.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Although it was potentially quicker, the proposal to deliver the antitoxin by flight was rejected by the board of health.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Instead, they voted unanimously for the dogsled relay.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was notified that evening and immediately began preparations for the trip.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Public Health Service had located 1.1 million units of serum in West Coast hospitals which could be shipped to Seattle, Washington, and then transported to Alaska.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The next ship north would not arrive in Seattle until January 31, and it would take another six to seven days to arrive in Seward.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On January 26, 300,000 forgotten units of the antitoxin were located in a hospital in Anchorage.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The supply was wrapped in glass vials, then padded quilts, and finally a metallic cylinder weighing a little over 20 pounds (9 kg).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] At Governor Scott Bone's order, it was immediately shipped to Nenana and arrived the next day.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While not sufficient to defeat the epidemic, the 300,000 units could slow the spread of the disease until the larger shipment arrived.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mail route from Nenana to Nome spanned 674 miles (1,085 km) in total.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] It crossed the barren Alaska Interior, following the Tanana River for 137 miles (220 km) to the village Tanana at the junction with the Yukon River, and then following the Yukon for 230 miles (370 km) to Kaltag.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The route then passed west 90 miles (140 km) over the Kaltag Portage to Unalakleet on the shore of Norton Sound.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The route then continued for 208 miles (335 km) northwest around the southern shore of the Seward Peninsula with no protection from gales and blizzards, including a 42-mile (68 km) stretch across the shifting ice of the Bering Sea.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Edward Wetzler, the US Postal Service inspector for Nenana, contacted Tom Parson, an agent of the Northern Commercial Company, contracted to deliver mail between Fairbanks and Unalakleet.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Telephones and telegraphs turned the drivers back to their assigned roadhouses.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mail carriers held a revered position in the territory, and were the best dog mushers in Alaska.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The majority of relay drivers across the Interior were native Athabaskans, direct descendants of the original dog mushers.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The first musher in the relay was "Wild Bill" Shannon, who was handed the 20 pounds (9 kg) package at the train station in Nenana on January 27 at 9:00 pm AKST by night.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite a temperature of −50 °F (−46 °C), Shannon left immediately with his team of 9 inexperienced dogs, led by Blackie.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature began to drop, and the team was forced onto the colder ice of the river because the trail had been destroyed by horses.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite jogging alongside the sled to keep warm, Shannon developed hypothermia.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He reached Minto at 3 am, with parts of his face black from frostbite.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After warming the serum by the fire and resting for four hours, Shannon dropped three dogs and left with the remaining 8.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The three dogs died shortly after Shannon returned for them, and a fourth may have died as well.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Half-Athabaskan Edgar Kalland arrived in Minto the night before, and was sent back to Tolovana, traveling 70 mi (110 km) the day before the relay.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Shannon and his team arrived in bad condition at 11 am, and handed over the serum.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After warming the serum in the roadhouse, Kalland headed into the forest.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature had fallen to −56 °F (−49 °C), causing Kalland's hands to freeze to the sled's handlebar, requiring the owner of the Manley Hot Springs roadhouse to pour boiling water on the birch wood bar for thawing.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] No new cases of diphtheria were diagnosed on January 28, but two new cases were diagnosed on January 29.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The quarantine had been obeyed, but lack of diagnostic tools and the contagiousness of the strain rendered it ineffective.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] More units of serum were discovered around Juneau the same day.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While no count exists, the estimate based on weight is roughly 125,000 units, enough to treat 4 to 6 patients.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The crisis had become headline news in newspapers, including in San Francisco, Cleveland, Washington D.C., and New York, and spread to the radio sets which were just becoming common.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The storm system from Alaska hit the contiguous United States, bringing record lows to New York, and freezing the Hudson River.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Maynard and Alaskan House Delegate Daniel Sutherland renewed their campaign for flying the remaining serum by plane.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Different proposals included flying a large aircraft 2,000 miles (3,200 km) from Seattle to Nome, carrying a plane to the edge of the pack ice via Navy ship and launching it, and the original plan of flying the serum from Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Despite receiving headline coverage across the country and support from Arctic explorer Roald Amundsen, the plans were rejected by experienced pilots, the Navy, and Governor Bone.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] As publisher and editor of the *Fairbanks Daily News-Miner* newspaper, William Fentress Thompson harshly criticized government officials for inaction and funded a private fleet of planes.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In response, Governor Bone decided to speed up the relay, authorizing additional drivers for Seppala's leg of the relay, so they could travel without rest.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was still scheduled to cover the most dangerous leg, the shortcut across Norton Sound, but the telephone and telegraph systems bypassed the small villages he was passing through, and there was no way to tell him to wait at Shaktoolik.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The plan relied on the driver from the north catching Seppala on the trail.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Summers arranged for drivers along the last leg, including Seppala's colleague Gunnar Kaasen.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] From Manley Hot Springs, the serum passed through largely Athabascan hands before George Nollner delivered it to Charlie Evans at Bishop Mountain on January 30 at 3 am.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature had warmed slightly, but at −62 °F (−52 °C), was dropping again.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Evans relied on his lead dogs when he passed through ice fog where the Koyukuk River, flowing into the Yukon, had broken through and surged over the ice, but forgot to protect the groins of his two short-haired mixed breed lead dogs with rabbit skins.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Both dogs collapsed with frostbite, with Evans having to take their place himself pulling the sled.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He arrived at 10 am; both dogs were dead.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Tommy Patsy departed within half an hour.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The transport of the serum then parted ways with the Yukon River as the river turned south and the trail crossed the Kaltag Portage west to the coast.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gonangnan saw the signs of a storm brewing, and decided not to take the shortcut across the dangerous ice of the Sound.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala was not there, but Henry Ivanoff was waiting just in case.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On January 30, the number of cases in Nome had reached 27 and the antitoxin was depleted.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] According to a reporter living in Nome, "All hope is in the dogs and their heroic drivers ...
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Nome appears to be a deserted city." With the report of Gonangnan's progress on January 31, Welch believed the serum would arrive there in February.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Leonhard Seppala and his dog sled team, with his lead dog Togo, travelled 91 miles (146 km) from Nome from January 27 to January 31 into the oncoming storm.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They took the shortcut across the Norton Sound, and headed toward Shaktoolik.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature in Nome was a relatively warm −20 °F (−29 °C), but in Shaktoolik, the temperature was estimated at −30 °F (−34 °C), and the gale force winds causing a wind chill of −85 °F (−65 °C).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Henry Ivanoff's team ran into a reindeer and got tangled up just outside Shaktoolik.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala still believed he had more than 100 mi (160 km) to the original relay point in Nulato to go and had raced to get off the Norton Sound before the storm hit.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was passing the team when Ivanoff shouted, "The serum!
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala turned around with the serum but it was dark by the time he got to Ungalik.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] But with the news of the worsening epidemic Ivanoff had shared, he decided not to stop and once again set out to brave the storm across the 20 miles (32 km) of exposed open ice of the Norton Sound.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The temperature was estimated at −30 °F (−34 °C), but the wind chill with the gale force winds was −85 °F (−65 °C).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo led the team in a straight line through the dark, and they arrived at the roadhouse in Isaac's Point on the other side at 8 pm.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In one day, they had travelled 84 mi (135 km), averaging 8 mph (13 km/h).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The team rested, and departed at 2 am into the full power of the storm.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] During the night, the temperature dropped to −40 °F (−40 °C), and the wind increased to storm force (at least 65 mph [105 km/h]).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While they slept, it had blown out to sea all the ice Seppala had just crossed.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] There was still some ice close to shore for the next part of their journey along the coast, but it was rough and starting to break up too.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They stuck close to shore, and Togo picked his way carefully until they were back on solid ground.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Next they had to cross Little McKinley Mountain (1,200 feet [370 m]), another of the toughest parts of the trail because of the many up-and-down ridges.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The total elevation climbed in that section of over 8 miles (13 km) is 5,000 feet (1,500 m).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After descending to the next roadhouse in Golovin, Seppala passed the serum to Charlie Olsen on February 1 at 3 pm.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On February 1, the number of cases in Nome rose to 28.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum en route was sufficient to treat 30 people.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] With the powerful blizzard raging and winds of 80 mph (130 km/h), Welch ordered a stop to the relay until the storm passed, reasoning that a delay was better than the risk of losing all the serum.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Messages were left at Solomon and Point Safety before the lines went dead.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Olsen was blown off the trail, and suffered severe frostbite in his hands while putting blankets on his dogs.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He arrived at Bluff on February 1 at 7 pm in poor condition.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gunnar Kaasen waited until 10 pm for the storm to break, but it only got worse and the drifts would soon block the trail, so he departed into a headwind.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen traveled through the night, through drifts, and river overflow over the 600-foot (183 m) Topkok Mountain.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto led the team through visibility so poor that Kaasen could not always see the dogs harnessed closest to the sled.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was two miles (3 km) past Solomon before he realized it, and kept going.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The winds after Solomon were so severe that his sled flipped over and he almost lost the cylinder containing the serum when it fell off and became buried in the snow.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also suffered frostbite when he had to use his bare hands to feel for the cylinder.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen reached Point Safety ahead of schedule on February 2, at 3 am.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ed Rohn believed that Kaasen and the relay had halted at Solomon, so he was sleeping.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Since the weather was improving, it would take time to prepare Rohn's team, and Balto and the other dogs were moving well, Kaasen pressed on with the remaining 25 miles (40 km) to Nome, reaching Front Street at 5:30 am.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Not a single ampule was broken, and the antitoxin was thawed and ready by noon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Together, the teams covered the 674 miles (1,085 km) in 1271⁄2 hours, which was considered a world record, done in extreme subzero temperatures in near-blizzard conditions and hurricane-force winds.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Margaret Curran from the Solomon Roadhouse was infected, which raised fears that the disease might spread from patrons of the roadhouse to other communities.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 1.1 million units had left Seattle on January 31, and were not due by dog sled until February 8.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Welch asked for half the serum to be delivered by aircraft from Fairbanks.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He contacted Thompson and Sutherland, and Darling made a test flight the next morning.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] With his health advisor, Governor Bone concluded the cases in Nome were actually going down, and withheld permission, but preparations went ahead.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Navy moved a minesweeper north from Seattle, and the Signal Corps were ordered to light fires to guide the planes.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] By February 3, the original 300,000 units had proved to be still effective, and the epidemic was under control.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A sixth death, probably unrelated to diphtheria, was widely reported as a new outbreak of the disease.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The batch from Seattle arrived on board the *Admiral Watson* on February 7.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Acceding to pressure, Governor Bone authorized half to be delivered by plane.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On February 8, the first half of the second shipment began its trip by dog sled, while the plane failed to start when a broken radiator shutter caused the engine to overheat.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The plane failed the next day as well, and the mission was scrapped.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Thompson was gracious in his editorials.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The second relay included many of the same drivers, and also faced harsh conditions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ed Rohn delivered the serum to Nome during another blizzard after a 90 miles (140 km) run on February 15.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The death toll from diphtheria in Nome is officially listed as either 5, 6, or 7, but Welch later estimated there were probably at least 100 additional cases among "the Eskimo camps outside the city.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The Natives have a habit of burying their children without reporting the death." Forty-three new cases were diagnosed in 1926, but they were easily managed with the fresh supply of serum.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] All participants in the dogsleds received letters of commendation from President Calvin Coolidge, and the Senate stopped work to recognize the event.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Each musher during the first relay received a gold medal from the H.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The mayor of Los Angeles presented a bone-shaped key to the city to Balto in front of City Hall and silent-film actress Mary Pickford put a wreath around the canine's neck.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Poems and letters from children poured in, and spontaneous fundraising campaigns sprang up around the country.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Gunnar Kaasen and his team became celebrities and toured the West Coast from February 1925 to February 1926, and also starred in a 30-minute film entitled *Balto's Race to Nome*.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A statue of Balto by sculptor Frederick Roth was unveiled in New York City's Central Park during a visit on December 15, 1925.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Balto and the other dogs later became part of a sideshow and lived in horrible conditions until they were rescued by George Kimble, who organized a fundraising campaign by the children of Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] On March 19, 1927, the dogs received a hero's welcome as they arrived at their permanent home at the Cleveland Zoo.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Because of his age, Balto was euthanized on March 14, 1933, at the age of 14.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He was mounted and placed on display in the Cleveland Museum of Natural History.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In October 1926, Seppala took Togo and his team on a tour from Seattle to California, and then across the Midwest to New England, and consistently drew huge crowds.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] They were featured at Madison Square Garden in New York City for 10 days, and Togo received a gold medal from Roald Amundsen.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In New England, Seppala's team of Siberians ran in many races, easily defeating the local Chinooks of Arthur Walden.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala entered into a partnership with Elizabeth M.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Ricker in Poland Spring, Maine, where many of his dogs went to live in retirement and contribute to their breeding program of Siberian sled dogs, including Togo, who sired many litters.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Seppala visited Togo, and was by his side when he was euthanized on December 5, 1929, at the age of 16.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] After his death, Seppala had Togo preserved and mounted, and today the dog is on display in a glass case at the Iditarod museum in Wasilla, Alaska.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Togo's prowess as a sled dog also led to his strengths being preserved through breeding, with his descendants contributing to the "Seppala Siberian Sleddog", a sought after working sled dog line, as well as the mainstream show-stock Siberian Husky gene pool.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] None of the other mushers received the same degree of attention, though Wild Bill Shannon briefly toured with Blackie.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The media largely ignored the Alaska Native mushers, who covered two-thirds of the distance to Nome.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum race helped spur the Air Mail Act of 1925, which was signed into law on February 2.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The bill allowed private aviation companies to bid on mail delivery contracts.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Technology improved and, within a decade, air mail routes were established in Alaska.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The last mail delivery by private dog sled under contract took place in 1938, and the last U.S.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Post Office dog sled route closed in 1963.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Dog sledding remained popular in the rural interior but became nearly extinct when snowmobiles spread in the 1960s.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Mushing was revitalized as a recreational sport in the 1970s with the immense popularity of the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] While the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, which runs more than 1,000 miles (1,600 km) from Anchorage to Nome, is based on the All-Alaska Sweepstakes, it has many traditions that commemorate the race to deliver the serum to Nome, especially Seppala and Togo.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The honorary musher for the first seven races was Leonhard Seppala.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Other serum run participants, including "Wild Bill" Shannon, Edgar Kalland, Bill McCarty, Charlie Evans, Edgar Nollner, Harry Pitka, and Henry Ivanoff have also been honored.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 2005 Iditarod honored Jirdes Winther Baxter, the last known survivor of the epidemic.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The position is now known as Leonhard Seppala's Honorary Musher, the Leonhard Seppala Humanitarian Award is given to the musher who provides the best dog care while remaining competitive, and the Leonhard Seppala Heritage Grant is an Iditarod scholarship.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The two races follow the same route from Ruby to Nome.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] A reenactment of the serum run was held in 1975, which took six days longer than the 1925 serum run, or more than twice the total time.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Many of the participants were descendants of the original 20.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1985, President Ronald Reagan sent a letter of recognition to Charlie Evans, Edgar Nollner, and Bill McCarty, the only remaining survivors.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Nollner was the last to die, on January 18, 1999, of a heart attack.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The relay has been depicted in various media.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Shortly before World War II, Czech teacher and writer František Omelka was fascinated by the story, writing the novella *Štafeta* ("Relay") published in Czech in 1946.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] As an avid Esperantist, Omelka himself translated it into Esperanto, with subsequent translations into German, Dutch, Frisian, Icelandic, Chinese, Japanese, and English.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The serum run was featured in the 1949 animated short "Daffy Duck Hunt", where Daffy Duck describes his time in a freezer as though he were delivering serum on a dog sled.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 1976, the story was retold in *Race Against Death: A True Story of the Far North,* by children's author Seymour Reit.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Reit's book was featured in a 1978 episode of *The Book Bird*, a PBS program where host John Robbins illustrated key scenes from the book being discussed.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The 1995 2D hand-drawn animated film *Balto* with music composed by James Roy Horner was loosely based on the events of the final leg of the serum run, although all of the characters besides Balto are fictional for family and children entertainments.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In 2013, a documentary titled *Icebound – The Greatest Dog Story Ever Told*, focused on the aftermath of the events.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] *The Great Alaskan Race*, a 2019 film, produced by Rebel Road Entertainment, is based on the serum run.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] *Togo*, produced by Walt Disney Pictures, debuted on December 20, 2019, on Disney+.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] There is much controversy surrounding Balto's role in the serum run and the statue in Central Park.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He then handed the serum off to Charlie Olson.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Olson carried it 25 miles (40 km) to Bluff where he turned it over to Gunnar Kaasen.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Kaasen was supposed to hand off the serum to Rohn at Port Safety, but Rohn had gone to sleep and Kaasen decided to keep going to Nome.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] In all, Kaasen and Balto ran a total of 53 miles (85 km).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] According to Togo's musher, Leonhard Seppala, who was also Balto's owner, Balto was a scrub freight dog that he left behind when he set out on the trip.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] He also asserted that Kaasen's lead dog was actually a dog named Fox, but that news agents of the time thought that Balto was a more newsworthy name.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] No record exists of Seppala ever having used Balto as a leader in runs or races prior to 1925, and Seppala himself stated Balto "was never in a winning team".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Because the pictures and video of Kaasen and Balto taken in Nome were recreated hours after their arrival once the sun had risen, speculation still exists as to whether Balto's position as lead dog was genuine, or was staged or exaggerated for media purposes.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] The Central Park statue of Balto was modeled after Balto, but shows him wearing Togo's colors (awards).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Katy Steinmetz, writing in *Time* magazine, also thought that Togo was the greatest sled dog of all time.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Mushers (in order) and the distances they covered.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1925-serum-run-to-nome] Most legs were planned to be about 25 miles (40 km) long, generally accepted as an "extreme day's mush".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] An election for a seat in the United States House of Representatives took place in California's 12th congressional district on November 5, 1946, the date set by law for the elections for the 80th United States Congress.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the 12th district election, the candidates were five-term incumbent Democrat Jerry Voorhis, Republican challenger Richard Nixon, and former congressman and Prohibition Party candidate John Hoeppel.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was elected with 56% of the vote, starting him on the road that would, almost a quarter century later, lead to the presidency.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] First elected to Congress in 1936, Voorhis had defeated lackluster Republican opposition four times in the then-rural Los Angeles County district to win re-election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] For the 1946 election, Republicans sought a candidate who could unite the party and run a strong race against Voorhis in the Republican-leaning district.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] After failing to secure the candidacy of General George Patton, in November 1945 they settled on Lieutenant Commander Richard Nixon, who had lived in the district prior to his World War II service.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon spent most of 1946 campaigning in the district, while Voorhis did not return from Washington D.C. until the end of August.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon's campaign worked hard to generate publicity in the district, while Voorhis, dealing with congressional business in the capital, received little newspaper coverage.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis received the most votes in the June primary elections, but his percentage of the vote decreased from his share in the 1944 primaries.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] At five debates held across the district in September and October, Nixon was able to paint the incumbent as ineffectual and to suggest that Voorhis was connected to communist-linked organizations.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis and his campaign were constantly on the defensive and were ineffective in rebutting Nixon's contentions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The challenger defeated Voorhis in the November general election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Various explanations have been put forward for Nixon's victory, from national political trends to red-baiting on the part of the challenger.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Some historians contend that Nixon received large amounts of funding from wealthy backers determined to defeat Voorhis, while others dismiss such allegations.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] These matters remain subjects of historical debate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Since its creation following the 1930 census, the 12th district had been represented by Democrats.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The 12th stretched from just south of Pasadena to the Orange and San Bernardino county lines, encompassing such small towns as Whittier, Pomona and Covina.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The area has since been entirely absorbed into the Los Angeles megalopolis, but at the time it was principally agricultural.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The freeway system had barely touched the 12th district; only a small segment of the Pasadena Freeway cut across its northwest corner.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1932, John Hoeppel was elected to represent the 12th district.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1936, Hoeppel was vulnerable as he had been convicted for trying to sell a nomination to West Point.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis defeated Hoeppel in the Democratic primary and easily won the general election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis, who gained a reputation as a respected and hard-working representative, nicknamed "Kid Atlas" by the press for taking the weight of the world on his shoulders, was loyal to the New Deal.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The 12th district leaned Republican, the more so after 1941 when the Republican-dominated California State Legislature attempted to gerrymander Congressman Voorhis out of office by removing strong Democratic precincts in East Los Angeles from the district during the decennial redistricting.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The revamped 12th district had little industry and almost no union influence.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis was left with such Republican strongholds as San Marino, where he did not campaign, concluding that he would receive the same number of votes whether he visited there or not.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Despite the maneuvers of the Republicans in the legislature, Voorhis was re-elected in 1942, receiving 57% of the vote, and won with a similar percentage two years later.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis had not faced strong opposition prior to 1946.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In his initial election, Voorhis benefited from the Roosevelt landslide of 1936.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] His 1938 opponent was so shy that Voorhis had to introduce him to the crowd at a joint appearance.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1940, he faced Captain Irwin Minger, a little-known commandant of a military school, and his 1942 opponent, radio preacher and former Prohibition Party gubernatorial candidate Robert P.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1944, the 12th district Republicans were bitterly divided, and Voorhis easily triumphed.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As Voorhis served his fifth term in the House, Republicans searched for a candidate capable of defeating him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Local Republicans formed what became known as the "Committee of One Hundred" (officially, the "Candidate and Fact-Finding Committee") to select a candidate with broad support in advance of the June 1946 primary election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Committee initially wooed State Commissioner of Education (and former Whittier College president) Walter Dexter.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Dexter was reluctant to give up his state post to run and sought a guarantee that he would receive another job if his candidacy failed.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He continued to consider running for several months without reaching a decision, frustrating local Republicans.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As Dexter dithered, Republicans tried to get General George Patton to run, though they were not certain if the general was a Republican.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] However, a day after the *Los Angeles Times* speculated on the run, Patton announced from Germany his intent to "keep completely out of politics".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Committee also contacted Stanley Barnes, a rising young Republican attorney and former football star at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Barnes declined to be considered, skeptical of the chances of defeating Voorhis.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] With little progress made on securing a high-profile candidate, Committee working groups held interviews.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Of the eight men who applied, the most prominent was former congressman John Hoeppel, who promised to keep "the Jews and the niggers" out of the district.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On October 6, 1945, the Monrovia *News Post* reported that while Dexter seemed the likely candidate, "of course anything can happen in politics and generally does".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The *News Post* stated that other names discussed by the Committee included "Lt. [*sic*] Richard Nixon, U.S.N.R., of Whittier." Congressman Voorhis wrote to his father and political adviser, Charles Voorhis, on October 15, "I understand the General has decided not to run in the 12th district.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Dexter would, in my opinion, be hard to beat.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When Dexter finally turned the Committee down, he recommended Nixon, his onetime student.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Dexter died only days later of a heart attack, and Patton died in an auto accident before the 1946 campaign began.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] At the time, Nixon was stationed in Baltimore, Maryland, using his legal training to deal with military contract terminations.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On November 1, 1945, he flew to California to meet influential Republicans and give a speech at a Committee meeting.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The meeting was advertised throughout the district and was open to any potential candidate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] However, the advertisements for the meeting noted that Nixon would be flying in to speak.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] A number of potential rivals also showed up at the meeting on November 2, 1945, including a local judge and assemblyman.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon, who spoke last, was "electrifying", according to one Committee member.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When the Committee met to vote on November 28, Nixon received over two-thirds of the vote, which was then made unanimous.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Committee chairman Roy Day immediately notified the victor of the Committee's endorsement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was already arranging to research Voorhis's record and to meet with Republican leaders in Washington, including House Minority Leader (and future Speaker) Joseph W.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The newly minted candidate wrote to Day regarding Voorhis, "His 'conservative' reputation must be blasted.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] But my main efforts are being directed toward building up a positive, progressive group of speeches which tell what we want to do, not what the Democrats have failed to do ...
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] I'm really hopped up over this deal, and I believe we can win." However, "wheelhorse" Republicans deemed Nixon's campaign hopeless.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was a virtual unknown outside of his hometown of Whittier and was facing a popular and respected incumbent.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Charles Voorhis wrote his son that the Republicans had endorsed a Quaker named Richard Nixon, but hoped that his son would retain a large part of the Quaker vote.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The elder Voorhis was confident that his son would triumph again, writing, "It is just another campaign that we have to go through ...
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was discharged from the Navy at the start of 1946.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Within days, he and his wife Pat Nixon, the latter almost eight months pregnant, returned to Whittier.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] They initially moved in with the candidate's parents, Frank and Hannah.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon returned to his old law firm, but spent most of his time campaigning.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Roy Day, chairman of the now-dissolved Committee, appointed himself as Nixon's campaign manager.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] This self-appointment dismayed the candidate somewhat, and Nixon unsuccessfully sought to replace Day.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis had been in Washington since August 1945, attending to congressional business.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He did not return to the district until August 1946, well after the June primary.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Beginning in February, the Republican hopeful began a heavy speaking schedule, addressing civic groups across the 400 square miles (1,000 km2) district.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon's efforts to get publicity were aided by the birth of his daughter Tricia in late February.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The new father was extensively interviewed and photographed with his infant daughter.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Congressman Voorhis's office sent the Nixons a government pamphlet entitled *Infant Care*, of which representatives received 150 per month to distribute to their constituents.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When Richard Nixon sent his rival a note of thanks in early April, the congressman responded with a letter proposing that the two debate once Congress adjourned in August.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In mid-March, Nixon was approached by former congressman Hoeppel, who hated Voorhis.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Hoeppel offered to enter the Democratic primary in exchange for a payment of several hundred dollars plus the promise of a civil service job once the Republican was elected.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] After consulting with his aides, Nixon turned him down.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Subsequently, Hoeppel filed as a Prohibition Party candidate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis was privy to these events through an informant close to the former representative, and was convinced that Roy Day had arranged to pay Hoeppel's filing fee.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The congressman feared that Hoeppel would serve as a stalking horse for Nixon, sparing the Republican from any "mudslinging".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis responded to Hoeppel's filing with a letter to his campaign manager, Baldwin Park realtor Jack Long, stating that "it would be worthwhile for us to try our level best to beat him in the Prohibition primary by a write-in campaign".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On March 18, two days before the filing deadline, Nixon filed in both the Republican and Democratic primaries under California's cross-filing system.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis also filed in the two major party primaries.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Under cross-filing, if the same candidate won both major party endorsements, he would be effectively elected, with only minor party candidates to stand against him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Day advanced the $200 (the current equivalent of $2,230) for Nixon's filing fees, later noting that he had great difficulty being reimbursed.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] By late March, Nixon's stock speeches to civic groups were becoming worn.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Day hired political consultant Murray Chotiner for $580 for the primary campaign, and the consultant warned that unless new life came into the campaign, it was in serious danger.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the following years, Chotiner was to become Nixon's campaign manager, adviser, and friend in an association that lasted until Chotiner's death a few months before President Nixon's 1974 resignation.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Chotiner arranged for stories in local papers alleging that Voorhis had been endorsed by "the PAC", hoping that voters would take that to mean the Congress of Industrial Organizations's Political Action Committee (CIO-PAC).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The CIO was a labor federation which later merged with the American Federation of Labor to form the AFL-CIO.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] It had been organized in 1943 and took left-wing stands; its PAC was seen as a communist front organization by some.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] A second PAC, the National Citizen's Political Action Committee (NCPAC) was also affiliated with the CIO, but was open to those outside the labor movement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Among the 1946 members of the NCPAC were actors Melvyn Douglas and Ronald Reagan.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Both PACs had been headed by the late labor leader, Sidney Hillman, and the two organizations shared office space in New York City.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] While the CIO's national leadership decried communism; some of the local CIO-PAC branches were dominated by Communist Party members.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The CIO-PAC, which had endorsed Voorhis in 1944, refused to back him again.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Southern California chapter of the NCPAC endorsed Voorhis on April 1, 1946.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Chotiner's strategy was to conflate the two PACs in the public eye.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nourished by the PAC controversy, the Republican campaign gained new life as Nixon returned to the lecture circuit.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] After Nixon spoke to a Lions Club meeting on May 1, a worried Voorhis supporter wrote to the congressman, "He carried the group by storm.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Both Voorhis and Nixon won his own party's primary, with Voorhis garnering a considerable number of votes in the Republican poll.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When all the votes from all primaries were added together, Voorhis outpolled Nixon by 7,000 votes.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis's total percentage of the vote decreased from 60% in the 1944 primaries to 53.5% in 1946.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Hoeppel survived the write-in campaign to advance to the general election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Following a two-week vacation in British Columbia after the primary, Nixon returned to the 12th district.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Republican began the general election campaign by replacing Roy Day with South Pasadena engineer Harrison McCall as campaign manager.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As Chotiner was increasingly distracted by his position as Southern California campaign manager for the (successful) reelection bid of Republican Senator William Knowland, the Nixon campaign added publicist William Arnold.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis, on the other hand, remained in Washington, dealing with Congressional business and generating little publicity.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He corresponded with his father and with his campaign manager, Jack Long, by letter.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis hoped to return to California in mid-August but while returning from Washington in August, he was forced to have surgery for hemorrhoids in Ogden, Utah.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis spent two weeks in an Ogden hotel recuperating from the operation and did not return to the district until the end of August.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis wrote later, "I can't say I was exactly 'ready for the fray'.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon did not reply to Voorhis's April debate proposal.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In May, the congressman wrote to Long as Nixon's campaign initially made the alleged PAC endorsement an issue.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis suggested that Nixon be challenged to debates as a matter of urgency.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Long responded in June, saying that though Nixon was known as a champion debater during his Whittier College days, "with your age and experience the general public might not take kindly to your challenging a boy like Nixon".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Long advised awaiting a challenge from Nixon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] By August, the two campaigns had settled on a debate to be held before a veteran's group in Whittier on September 20.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] However, the "Independent Voters of South Pasadena" (IVSP), headed by future Voorhis biographer Paul Bullock, announced a September 13 town meeting on campaign issues at South Pasadena Junior High School.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The IVSP's actual purpose in having the meeting was to get a vulnerable Republican assemblyman (who declined his invitation) to debate his Democratic rival, but Senate and 12th district Republican and Democratic candidates were invited.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Given that the debate sponsors were liberals, some of Nixon's aides advised him to refuse, but he overrode them.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Holifield of the neighboring 19th district.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The town meeting attracted a packed crowd of over a thousand, with Nixon supporters distributing anti-Voorhis literature at the door.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Senate proxies spoke first for their candidates, followed by Voorhis.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon, who had notified organizers that he would be late due to another commitment, arrived during Voorhis's speech, and remained backstage until the congressman had completed his talk.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He then came onstage, shook hands with Voorhis, and delivered a fifteen-minute address.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] A question-and-answer period then followed, with a Nixon supporter asking Voorhis about his onetime Socialist registration, and about his views on monetary policy.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] After the representative responded, a Voorhis supporter asked Nixon why he was making "false charges" about the supposed Voorhis CIO-PAC endorsement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In response, Nixon reached into his pocket and pulled out a copy of a Southern California NCPAC bulletin mentioning the group's endorsement of Voorhis.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The congressman was unaware of the endorsement; those of his aides in the know had "completely forgotten" to tell him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon walked halfway across the stage and displayed it to Voorhis, asking him to read it for himself.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis came from his seat and took it, and (according to Bullock, who served as timekeeper at the debate) "mumbled" that this seemed to be a different organization from the CIO-PAC.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the midst of the turmoil, Prohibition Party candidate Hoeppel came down the aisle (according to Bullock, possibly drunk) and demanded to know why he had been excluded from the debate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He was permitted to ask one question, of Voorhis, and the evening ended.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On September 19, Voorhis wired the NCPAC's Los Angeles and New York offices, requesting that "whatever qualified endorsement the Citizens PAC may have given me be withdrawn".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] By this time, newspapers across the district had printed Nixon's charges, along with a Nixon advertisement castigating Voorhis for allegedly accusing Nixon of lying about the PAC endorsement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Nixon biographer Roger Morris, the repudiation of NCPAC endorsements did not help Voorhis, as his actions "would seem to many a half-guilty shedding of sinister backing he never had.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The second debate was held at Patriotic Hall in Whittier on September 20.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As the debate was sponsored by the Whittier Ex-Servicemen's Association, attendance was limited to veterans.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The candidates debated the best way of dealing with the postwar housing shortage.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis favored restricting building of commercial structures to free up materials for housing, while Nixon urged the removal of all building restrictions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] When Nixon repeated his PAC allegations, Voorhis noted his request to the NCPAC, stating that he could not be held responsible for its actions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Morris, the debate ended as a draw, or perhaps even a Voorhis victory.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Chotiner convinced Nixon that he needed to run an aggressive campaign to the end, and McCall challenged the Voorhis campaign to as many as eight additional debates, of which three were actually held.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The debates captured the interest of the public in the district and attracted large crowds.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The candidates were compared to Abraham Lincoln and Stephen Douglas, who had famously debated in their 1858 senatorial campaign, and bands played marches as each candidate entered the venue.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The two candidates' third meeting was held at Bridges Auditorium in Claremont on October 11.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis was, by his own admission, "awfully tired".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The candidates discussed labor policy, and Nixon "scored" by detailing a policy for dealing with public strikes that Voorhis too late realized was taken from a bill he had drafted.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon took Voorhis aside after the debate and lambasted him for addressing him as "Lieutenant Commander Nixon", accusing him of pandering to former enlisted men's dislike of officers.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the fourth debate, on October 23 at Monrovia High School, Nixon attacked Voorhis's congressional record.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The challenger alleged that in the previous four years, Voorhis only had been able to pass a single bill through Congress and into law.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The bill in question transferred jurisdiction over rabbit farming from the Department of the Interior to the Department of Agriculture.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon chided, "One has to be a rabbit to get effective representation in this congressional district." Voorhis responded that he had sponsored an act to employ the physically handicapped, but Nixon stated that it was not a law, but a joint resolution.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon restated his allegation regarding Voorhis and the PAC; Voorhis retorted that he had repudiated the NCPAC endorsement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon parried with a comment that Voorhis's voting record "earned him the endorsement, whether he wanted it or not".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon also contended that in 46 votes, Voorhis had almost entirely followed the CIO-PAC agenda.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Distraught, Voorhis stayed up until 4 am studying the votes Nixon had taxed him with.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He concluded that due to duplications, there were actually only 27 roll calls in question, on many of which he had opposed the CIO-PAC position.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The congressman also found that the votes "friendly" to the CIO-PAC included one authorizing a school lunch program.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The final debate took place October 28 at the San Gabriel Civic Auditorium, to an overflow crowd in excess of a thousand.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis went on the attack, charging Nixon with misrepresenting the "46 votes" to avoid real debate and any discussion of where Nixon himself stood on issues.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Republican candidate stated that he was fighting for "the person on a pension trying to keep up with the rising cost of living ... the white-collar worker who has not had a raise ...
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In mid October, the Nixon campaign unveiled an advertisement which foreshadowed his run for Senate four years later.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1950, a similar comparison between the voting record of Marcantonio and Democratic Senate nominee Douglas, printed on pink paper, came to be known as the "Pink Sheet".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Nixon campaign continued to run newspaper ads touching on the PAC issue.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] One ad suggested Radio Moscow had urged the election of the CIO slate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Others touched on Voorhis's past registration as a Socialist, and stated that his congressional record "is more Socialistic and Communistic than Democratic".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Democrats brought James Roosevelt and other prominent Democrats into the district to campaign for Voorhis.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon proposed that his wartime acquaintance, former Minnesota Governor Harold Stassen campaign for him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] However, the candidate could not get permission from the California Republican committee for Stassen to visit.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis publicized a letter he had received from the Republican governor, Earl Warren, praising him for a disability insurance proposal he had made.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon supporters asked Warren for a letter praising Nixon, or at least a retraction of the Voorhis letter.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Warren refused, saying that Voorhis deserved the compliment, and Nixon would not receive an endorsement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] This conflict began a contentious relationship between Nixon and Warren which lasted until Warren's death shortly before Nixon's resignation as president.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] No polls had been taken during the campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] On election night, Voorhis took an early lead in the vote count, but was soon overtaken by his challenger, whose margin increased as the night went on.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon defeated Voorhis by over 15,000 votes.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Republican won 19 of the 22 municipalities in the district, including Voorhis's home town of San Dimas.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis won the Democratic strongholds of El Monte and Monterey Park, as well as rural Baldwin Park.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] *Time* magazine's post-election issue came out in mid-November, and it praised the future president for "politely avoid[ing] personal attacks on his opponent".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Despite any hard feelings, Voorhis sent Nixon a letter of congratulations in early December 1946.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon and Voorhis met for an hour at Voorhis's office, and parted, according to Voorhis, as friends.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1971, Voorhis said that the two had never spoken again.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis's final letter as a congressman, written on December 31, was to his father, who had been his political adviser throughout his congressional career.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Representative Voorhis wrote, "It has been primarily due to your help, your confidence, your advice ... above all to a feeling I have always had that your hand was on my shoulder.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis never ran again for political office, working as an executive in the cooperative movement for twenty years after his defeat.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Hoeppel continued as publisher and editor of *National Defense* magazine, a publication for veterans, until his 1960 retirement, and died in Arcadia in 1976 at age 95.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon served two terms in the House, and in 1950 was elected to the United States Senate, continuing his political rise, which would lead him to the White House in 1969.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The 12th district race of 1946 was little noticed at the time.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] As Nixon became prominent, the 1946 race was scrutinized more closely.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon's defeat of Voorhis has been cited as the first of a number of red-baiting campaigns by the future president which elevated him to the House, the Senate, the Vice Presidency, and eventually put him in position to run for president.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon, in his 1978 memoir, stated that the central issue in the 1946 campaign was "the quality of life in postwar America", and he won because voters "had 'had enough,' and they decided to do something about it".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis, in his 1947 memoir, indicated that the "most important single factor in the campaign of 1946 was the difference in general attitude between the 'outs' and the 'ins'.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In later years, Voorhis had more to say about the reasons for his defeat.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1958, he alleged that voters had received anonymous phone calls saying that he was a communist, that newspapers had stated that he was a fellow traveler, and that when Nixon got angry, he would "do anything".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In November 1962, after Nixon's defeat in the California gubernatorial race, Voorhis appeared on Howard K.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Smith's *News and Comment* program on ABC in the episode entitled "The Political Obituary of Richard M.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon" and complained about the way Nixon had conducted himself in the 1946 race.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis's appearance was overshadowed by the controversial participation of Nixon adversary Alger Hiss.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1972, Voorhis authored a book, *The Strange Case of Richard Milhous Nixon*, in which he stated that Nixon was "quite a ruthless opponent" whose "one cardinal and unbreakable rule of conduct" was "to win, whatever it takes to do it".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1981, three years before his death, Voorhis denied in an interview that he had been endorsed by the NCPAC.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In an early draft of his memoir, Voorhis wrote that he had documentation showing that "the Nixon campaign was a creature of big eastern financial interests".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon biographer Irwin Gellman, writing in 1999, nine years after Morris, disagreed with the latter's conclusions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Gellman argued that the Committee was a "grassroots" group which was "far from sophisticated" in its efforts to find a candidate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Parmet wrote that the campaign was not well financed, "Nixon had to learn that money would be scarce until he became a winner ...
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The Nixon campaign of 1946 *did* look like a shoestring affair." Aitken points out that Nixon spent no money on radio advertising during the campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Other allegations center on Murray Chotiner, painting him as the "evil genius" of the campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Part of this inflation is due to Chotiner himself, who, in later years, lost no opportunity to exaggerate his role in the 1946 race, to the annoyance of Day and McCall.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Nixon biographer Stephen Ambrose, "Nevertheless, the legend grew.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the eyes of Nixon's critics, as a candidate he was merely a front man for Chotiner's evil manipulations.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] A number of biographies on Nixon or Voorhis, or which otherwise touch on the 1946 campaign, state with varying degrees of certainty that during the final weekend of the campaign, anonymous calls were made to district households.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The caller would ask "Did you know Jerry Voorhis is a communist?" and then hang up.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Bullock, there was a phone bank staffed by workers who had responded to a newspaper ad, run by the Nixon organization in Alhambra.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Bullock cites as his source for this Zita Remley, a "Voorhis admirer", who stated that her niece had worked there.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Although the niece died before Bullock's book was written, according to Bullock, Remley's "reputation for veracity is unchallengeable".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon spent most of 1946 campaigning in the district, and worked hard to extend his name recognition beyond his hometown of Whittier.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Starting in the primary, the Nixon campaign made determined efforts to woo the district's newspapers.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The campaign targeted smaller papers, especially the small weekly newspapers that were distributed for free; Republican surveys found that these were widely read and trusted.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon supporter and Republican National Committeeman from California McIntyre Faries arranged to buy ads on behalf of the Nixon campaign on condition that the newspaper run an editorial at its direction (most of the papers were, in any event, Republican in their outlook).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] These efforts paid off; 26 of the 30 newspapers serving the district endorsed Nixon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Nixon biographer Morris, Voorhis was given no coverage in newspapers, or limited to small paid advertisements.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] The paper owners told the Voorhis campaign that, with the postwar paper shortage, space had to be saved for regular customers.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Voorhis's campaign, described by Bullock as "traditionally amateurish and poorly put together", was slow to perceive the threat presented by Nixon and remained continually on the defensive.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In 1971, in an article marking the 25th anniversary of the campaign, Voorhis acknowledged that "I never had much of an organization; frankly, there was no form to it.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] And we needed it badly in 1946." In the same article, the *Los Angeles Times* described Voorhis's campaign as "undermanned, underfinanced, outgunned, outmaneuvered and he apparently was on the wrong side of most of the issues of the day".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] His one avenue of outreach in the press was his newspaper column, *People's Business*, which ran in most local newspapers.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In July 1946, Voorhis chose to suspend this column lest it be thought that he was using it as a means of campaigning.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] According to Gellman, this weakened Voorhis's political outreach.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] One blunder identified by Gellman was Voorhis's decision to debate Nixon, as it raised the challenger's profile to the same level as the incumbent's.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] This decision was described by Morris as "quiet hubris".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1946-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Rather than return to campaign in the primary when he recognized Nixon's attractiveness, he remained in the capital, allowing Nixon to court newspaper publishers and reporters as well as constituents who wanted to have firsthand contact with their congressional representative.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] An election for a seat in the United States House of Representatives took place in California's 12th congressional district on November 2, 1948, the date set by law for the elections for the 81st United States Congress.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In the 12th district election, the candidates were one-term incumbent Republican Richard Nixon, and Progressive challenger Una W.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon was reelected with 87% of the vote.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] In June, Nixon won the Republican primary uncontested, as well as the Democratic primary, defeating attorney Stephen I.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon would have gone on to the general election without an opponent, but because no members of the Independent Progressive Party ran in the primary, the party was later able to select Rosemead housewife Una W.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Rice boasted endorsements from the Pomona AFL Central labor Council, the Los Angeles CIO-PAC, and the California State Brotherhood of Locomotive Firemen and Enginemen.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] For his part, Nixon was so sure of his victory that he took time out of his own campaign to go on a nationwide speaking tour for Republican Presidential candidate Thomas E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] Nixon spent election night with his family at the Ambassador Hotel's Cocoanut Grove, where he was invited onstage by singer Hildegarde.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1948-california-s-12th-congressional-district-election] He was ultimately reelected in a landslide.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The **1950 United States Senate election in California** was held on November 7 of that year, following a campaign characterized by accusations and name-calling.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Republican Representative and future President Richard Nixon defeated Democrat Representative Helen Gahagan Douglas, after Democratic incumbent Sheridan Downey withdrew during the primary election campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas and Nixon each gave up their congressional seats to run against Downey; no other representatives were willing to risk the contest.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Both Douglas and Nixon announced their candidacies in late 1949.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In March 1950, Downey withdrew from a vicious primary battle with Douglas by announcing his retirement, after which Los Angeles *Daily News* publisher Manchester Boddy joined the race.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy attacked Douglas as a leftist and was the first to compare her to New York Representative Vito Marcantonio, who was accused of being a communist.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy, Nixon, and Douglas each entered both party primaries, a practice known as cross-filing.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In the Republican primary, Nixon was challenged only by cross-filers and fringe candidates.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon won the Republican primary and Douglas the Democratic contest, with each also finishing third in the other party's contest (Boddy finished second in both races).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The contentious Democratic race left the party divided, and Democrats were slow to rally to Douglas—some even endorsed Nixon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The Korean War broke out only days after the primaries, and both Nixon and Douglas contended that the other had often voted with Marcantonio to the detriment of national security.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon's attacks were far more effective, and he won the November 7 general election by almost 20 percentage points, carrying 53 of California's 58 counties and all metropolitan areas.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Though Nixon was later criticized for his tactics in the campaign, he defended his actions, and also stated that Douglas's positions were too far to the left for California voters.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Other reasons for the result have been suggested, ranging from tepid support for Douglas from President Harry S.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Truman and his administration to the reluctance of voters in 1950 to elect a woman.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The campaign gave rise to two political nicknames, both coined by Boddy or making their first appearance in his newspaper: "the Pink Lady" for Douglas and "Tricky Dick" for Nixon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] California Senator Sheridan Downey was first elected in 1938.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] An attorney, he had run unsuccessfully in 1934 for Lieutenant Governor of California as Upton Sinclair's running mate, and had a reputation as a liberal.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] As a senator, however, his positions gradually moved to the right, and he began to favor corporate interests.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Manchester Boddy, the editor and publisher of the Los Angeles *Daily News*, was born on a potato farm in Washington state.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He had little newspaper experience when, in 1926, he was given the opportunity to purchase the *Daily News* by a bankruptcy court, but built it into a small but thriving periodical.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He shared his views with his readers through his column, "Thinking and Living", and, after initial Republican leanings, was a firm supporter of the New Deal.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] While the *Daily News* had not endorsed the Sinclair–Downey ticket, Boddy had called Sinclair "a great man" and allowed the writer-turned-gubernatorial candidate to set forth his views on the newspaper's front page.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Both Helen Douglas and Richard Nixon entered electoral politics in the mid-1940s.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas, a New Deal Democrat, was a former actress and opera singer, and the wife of actor Melvyn Douglas.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She represented the 14th congressional district beginning in 1945.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon grew up in a working-class family in Whittier.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1946, he defeated 12th district Representative Jerry Voorhis to claim a seat in the United States House of Representatives in January 1947, where he became known for his anticommunist activities, including his involvement in the Alger Hiss affair.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In the 1940s, California experienced a huge influx of migrants from other US states, increasing its population by 55%.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Party registration in 1950 was 58.4% Democratic and 37.1% Republican.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] However, other than Downey, most major California officeholders were Republican, including Governor Earl Warren (who was seeking a third term in 1950) and Senator William Knowland.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] During the 1950 campaign, both Nixon and Douglas were accused of having a voting record comparable to that of New York Representative Vito Marcantonio.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The sole representative from the American Labor Party at the time, Marcantonio represented East Harlem.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He was accused of being a communist, though he denied being one; he rarely discussed the Soviet Union or communism.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Marcantonio opposed restrictions on communists and the Communist Party, stating that such restrictions violated the Bill of Rights.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He regularly voted against contempt citations requested by the House Un-American Activities Committee (HUAC), on which Nixon served.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas disregarded advice from party officials to wait until 1952 to run for the Senate, when Republican Senator Knowland would be up for reelection.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Fundraising for the campaign was a concern from the beginning; Douglas friend and aide Ed Lybeck wrote her that she would probably need to raise $150,000 ($1.8 million today), which Douglas considered a massive sum.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On October 5, 1949, Douglas made a radio appearance announcing her candidacy.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She attacked Downey almost continuously throughout the remainder of the year, accusing him of being a do-nothing, a tool of big business, and an agent of oil interests.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She hired Harold Tipton, a newcomer to California who had managed a successful congressional campaign in the Seattle area, as her campaign manager.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas realized that Nixon would most likely be the Republican nominee, and felt that were she to win the primary, the wide gap between Nixon's positions and hers would cause voters to rally to her.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Downey, who suffered from a severe ulcer, was initially undecided about running, but announced his candidacy in early December in a speech that included an attack on Douglas.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Earl Desmond, a member of the California State Senate from Sacramento whose positions were similar to Downey's, also entered the race.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In January 1950, Douglas opened campaign headquarters in Los Angeles and San Francisco, which was seen as a signal that she was serious about contesting Downey's seat and would not withdraw from the race.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Downey challenged Douglas to a series of debates; Douglas, who was not a good debater, declined.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The two candidates traded charges via press and radio, with Downey describing Douglas's views as extremist.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's formal campaign launch on February 28 was overshadowed by rumors that Downey might retire, which Douglas called a political maneuver on Downey's part to get the attention of the press.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] However, on March 29, amid rumors that he was doing badly in the polls, Downey announced both his retirement and his endorsement of Los Angeles *Daily News* publisher Manchester Boddy.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In his statement, the senator indicated that, due to his ill health, he was not up to "waging a personal and militant campaign against the vicious and unethical propaganda" of Douglas.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy filed his election paperwork the next day, on the final day petitions were accepted, with his papers signed by Los Angeles Mayor Fletcher Bowron, a Republican, and by Downey campaign manager and 1946 Democratic senatorial candidate Will Rogers Jr.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The publisher had been urged to enter the race by state Democratic leaders and by wealthy oilmen.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He had no political experience; Democratic leaders had sought to draft him to run for the Senate in 1946, but he had declined.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He later stated that his reasons for running were that the race would be a challenge, and that he would meet interesting people.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy, Douglas, and Nixon each "cross-filed", entering both major party primaries.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas called Downey's departure in favor of the publisher a cheap gimmick and made no attempt to reach a *rapprochement* with the senator, who entered Bethesda Naval Hospital for treatment in early April, and was on sick leave from Congress for several months.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The change in opponents was a mixed blessing for Douglas; it removed the incumbent from the field, but deprived her of the endorsement of the *Daily News*—one of the few big city papers to consistently support her.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] For the first month of Boddy's abbreviated ten-week campaign, he and Douglas avoided attacking each other.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy's campaign depicted him as born in a log cabin, and highlighted his World War I service.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The publisher campaigned under the slogan, "Manchester Boddy, the Democrat Every Body Wants." Boddy stated that he was fighting for the "little man", and alleged that the average individual was overlooked by both big government and big labor.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] However, his campaign, having a late start, was disorganized.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The candidate himself had little charisma, and little presence as a public speaker.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] According to Rob Wagner, who wrote of the campaign in his history of Los Angeles newspapers of the era, Boddy "was all sizzle and no substance".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The campaign calm broke off near the end of April 1950, when Boddy's *Daily News* and affiliated newspapers referred to the congresswoman as "decidedly pink" and "pink shading to deep red".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] At the end of the month, the *Daily News* referred to her for the first time as "the pink lady".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas generally ignored Boddy's attacks, which continued unabated through May.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In a *Daily News* column, Boddy wrote that Douglas was part of "a small minority of red hots" which proposed to use the election to "establish a beachhead on which to launch a Communist attack on the United States".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] One Boddy campaign publication was printed with red ink, and stated that Douglas "has too often teamed up with the notorious extreme radical, Vito Marcantonio of New York City, on votes that seem more in the interest of Soviet Russia than of the United States".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On May 3, Representative George Smathers defeated liberal Senator Claude Pepper for the Democratic Senate nomination in Florida.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Smathers' tactics included dubbing his opponent "Red Pepper" and distributing red-covered brochures, *The Red Record of Senator Claude Pepper*, that included a photograph of Pepper with Marcantonio.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Soon after Smathers' triumph in the primary, which in the days of the yellow dog South was tantamount to election, South Dakota Republican Senator Karl Mundt, who when in the House had served with Nixon on HUAC, sent him a letter telling him about Smathers' brochure.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Downey reentered the fray on May 22, when he made a statewide radio address on behalf of Boddy, stating his belief that Douglas was not qualified to be a senator.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He concluded, "Her record clearly shows very little hard work, no important influence on legislation, and almost nothing in the way of solid achievement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas brought an innovation to the race—a small helicopter, which she used to travel around the state at a time when there were few freeways linking California's cities.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She got the idea from her friend, Texas Senator and future President Lyndon Johnson, who had extensively used helicopters in his campaign during the heavily contested Democratic Party primary for the 1948 United States Senate election in Texas.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas leased the craft from a helicopter company in Palo Alto owned by Republican supporters, who hoped her influence would lead to a defense contract.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] When she used it to land in San Rafael, her local organizer, Dick Tuck, called it the "Helencopter", and the name stuck.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In early April, polls gave Nixon some chance of winning the Democratic primary, which would mean his election was secured.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He sent out mailings to Democratic voters.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy attacked Nixon for the mailings; Nixon responded that Democratic voters should have the opportunity to express no confidence in the Truman administration by voting for a Republican.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] "Democrats for Nixon", a group affiliated with Nixon's campaign, asked Democratic voters "as one Democrat to another" to vote for the congressman, sending out flyers which did not mention his political affiliation.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy quickly struck back in his paper, accusing Nixon of misrepresenting himself as a Democrat.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A large ad in the same issue by the "Veterans Democratic Committee" warned Democratic voters that Nixon was actually a Republican and referred to him for the first time as "Tricky Dick".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The exchange benefited neither Nixon nor Boddy; Douglas won the primary on June 6 and exceeded their combined vote total.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In mid-1949, Nixon, although anxious to advance his political career, was reluctant to run for the Senate unless he was confident of winning the Republican primary.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He considered his party's prospects in the House to be bleak, absent a strong Republican trend, and wrote "I seriously doubt if we can ever work our way back in power.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In late August 1949, Nixon embarked on a putatively nonpolitical speaking tour of Northern California, where he was less well known, to see if his candidacy would be well received if he ran.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] With many of his closest advisers urging him to do so, Nixon decided in early October to seek the Senate seat.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He hired a professional campaign manager, Murray Chotiner, who had helped to run successful campaigns for both Governor Warren and Senator Knowland and had played a limited role in Nixon's first congressional race.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon announced his candidacy in a radio broadcast on November 3, painting the race as a choice between a free society and state socialism.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner's philosophy for the primary campaign was to focus on Nixon and ignore the opposition.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon did not indulge in negative campaigning in the primaries; according to Nixon biographer Irwin Gellman, the internecine warfare in the Democratic Party made it unnecessary.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The Nixon campaign spent most of late 1949 and early 1950 concentrating on building a statewide organization, and on intensive fundraising, which proved successful.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon had built part of his reputation in the House on his role in the Alger Hiss affair.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Hiss's retrial for perjury after a July 1949 hung jury was a cloud over Nixon's campaign; if Hiss was acquitted, Nixon's candidacy would be in serious danger.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On January 21, 1950, the jury found Hiss guilty, and Nixon received hundreds of congratulatory messages, including one from the only living former president, Herbert Hoover.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Houser eventually decided against running.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Los Angeles County Supervisor Raymond Darby commenced a Senate run, but changed his mind and instead ran for lieutenant governor.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Darby was defeated by incumbent Lieutenant Governor Goodwin Knight in the Republican primary.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Knight had also been considered likely to run for the Senate, but decided to seek re-election instead.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Actor Edward Arnold began a Senate run, but dropped it in late March, citing a lack of time to prepare his campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On March 20, Nixon cross-filed in the two major party primaries, and two weeks later began to criss-cross the state in his campaign vehicle: a yellow station wagon with "Nixon for U.S.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] According to one contemporary news account, in his "barnstorming tour", Nixon intended to "[talk] up his campaign for the U.S.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Senate on street corners and wherever he can collect a crowd." During his nine-week primary tour, he visited all of California's 58 counties, speaking sometimes six or eight times in a day.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] His wife Pat Nixon stood by as her husband spoke, distributing campaign thimbles that urged the election of Nixon and were marked with the slogan "Safeguard the American Home".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She distributed more than 65,000 by the end of the campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] With no serious challenge from Republican opponents, Nixon won an overwhelming victory in the Republican primary, with his cross-filing rivals, Boddy, Douglas, and Desmond, dividing a small percentage of the vote but running well ahead of the two fringe candidates.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] There were no candidate debates, but Douglas and Nixon met twice on the campaign trail during the primary season.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The first meeting took place at the Commonwealth Club in San Francisco, where Nixon waved a check for $100 that his campaign had received from "Eleanor Roosevelt", with an accompanying letter, "I wish it could be ten times more.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Best wishes for your success." The audience was shocked at the idea of Eleanor Roosevelt, widow of Democratic former president Franklin Roosevelt and known for her liberal views, contributing to Nixon's campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon went on to explain that the envelope was postmarked Oyster Bay, New York, and that the Eleanor Roosevelt who had sent the contribution was Eleanor Butler Roosevelt, the widow of former Republican president Theodore Roosevelt's eldest son.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The audience laughed, and Douglas later wrote that she had been distracted and gave a poor speech.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A memo from Chotiner several days later noted that Boddy had failed to attend the function, and that Douglas wished that she had also not attended.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A second joint appearance took place in Beverly Hills.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] According to Nixon campaign adviser Bill Arnold, Douglas arrived late, while Nixon was already speaking.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon ostentatiously looked at his watch, provoking laughter from the audience.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The laughter recurred as Nixon, sitting behind Douglas as she spoke, fidgeted to indicate his disapproval of what she was saying; she appeared bewildered at the laughter.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas concluded her remarks and Nixon rose to speak again, but she did not stay to listen.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The rift in the Democratic party caused by the primary was slow to heal; Boddy's supporters were reluctant to join Douglas's campaign, even with President Truman's encouragement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The President refused to campaign in California; he resented Democratic gubernatorial candidate James Roosevelt.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Roosevelt, the eldest son of Franklin Roosevelt, had urged Democrats not to nominate Truman in 1948, but to instead choose General Dwight Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Fundraising continued to be a major problem for Douglas, the bulk of whose financial support came from labor unions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The weekend after the primary, Nixon campaign officials held a conference to discuss strategy for the general election campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] They decided on a fundraising goal of just over $197,000 (today, about $2,400,000).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] They were helped in that effort when Democratic Massachusetts Congressman John F.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Kennedy, a political opponent of Nixon's, came to Nixon's office and gave him a donation of $1,000 on behalf of Joseph P.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] John Kennedy indicated that he could not endorse Nixon, but that he would not be heartbroken if Douglas was returned to her acting career.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Joseph Kennedy later stated that he gave Nixon the money because Douglas was a communist.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon's positions generally favored large corporations and farming interests, while Douglas's did not, and Nixon reaped the reward with contributions from them.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon favored the Taft–Hartley Act, passage of which had been bitterly opposed by labor unions; Douglas advocated its repeal.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas supported a requirement that federally subsidized water from reclamation projects only go to farms of not more than 160 acres (0.65 km2); Nixon fought for the repeal of that requirement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] When the Korean War broke out in late June, Douglas and her aides feared being put on the defensive by Nixon on the subject of communism, and sought to preempt his attack.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's opening campaign speech included a charge that Nixon had voted with Marcantonio to deny aid to South Korea and to cut aid to Europe in half.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon objected to Douglas's speech, stating that he had opposed the Korea bill because it did not include aid to Taiwan, and had supported it once the aid had been included.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] As for the Europe charge, according to Nixon biographer Stephen Ambrose, Nixon was so well known as a supporter of the Marshall Plan that Douglas's charge had no credibility.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In fact, Nixon had opposed a two-year reauthorization of the Marshall Plan, favoring a one-year reauthorization with a renewal provision, allowing for more congressional oversight.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon realized that the battle in California would be fought over the threat of communism, and his campaign staff began to research Douglas's voting record.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Republican officials in Washington sent the campaign a report listing 247 times Marcantonio (who generally followed the Democratic line) and Douglas had voted together, and 11 times that they had not.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Public support for the Korean War initially resulted in anger towards communists, and Nixon advocated the passage of legislation he had previously introduced with Senator Mundt which would tighten restrictions on communists and the Communist Party.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas argued that there was already sufficient legislation to effect any necessary prosecutions, and that the Mundt–Nixon bill (soon replaced by the similar McCarran–Wood bill) would erode civil liberties.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] With the bill sure to pass, Douglas was urged to vote in favor to provide herself with political cover.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She declined to do so, though fellow California Representative Chester E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Holifield warned her that she would not be able to get around the state fast enough to explain her vote and Nixon would "beat [her] brains in".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas was one of only 20 representatives (including Marcantonio) who voted against the bill.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Truman vetoed it; Congress enacted it over his veto by wide margins in late September.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas was one of 47 representatives (including Marcantonio) to vote to sustain the veto.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In a radio broadcast soon after the veto override, Douglas announced that she stood with the President, Attorney General J.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Edgar Hoover in their fight against communism.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On September 10, Eleanor Roosevelt, the late president's widow and the gubernatorial candidate's mother, arrived in California for a quick campaign swing to support her son and Douglas before she had to return to New York as a delegate to the United Nations.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas hoped that the former first lady's visit would mark a turning point in the campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Roosevelt the next day in Long Beach, Nixon workers first handed out a flyer headed "Douglas–Marcantonio Voting Record", printed with dark ink on pink paper.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The legal-size flyer compared the voting records of Douglas and Marcantonio, principally in the area of national security, and concluded that they were indistinguishable.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In contrast, the flyer said, Nixon had voted entirely in opposition to the "Douglas–Marcantonio Axis".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] It implied that sending Douglas to the Senate would be no different from electing Marcantonio, and asked if that was what Californians wanted.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The paper soon became known as the "Pink Sheet".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner later stated that the color choice was made at the print shop when campaign officials approved the final copy, and "for some reason or other it just seemed to appeal to us for the moment".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] An initial print run of 50,000 was soon followed by a reprint of 500,000, distributed principally in heavily populated Southern California.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas made no immediate response to the Pink Sheet, despite the advice of Mrs.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Roosevelt, who appreciated its power and urged her to answer it.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas later stated that she had failed to understand the appeal of the Pink Sheet to voters, and simply thought it absurd.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon followed up on the Pink Sheet with a radio address on September 18, accusing Douglas of being "a member of a small clique which joins the notorious communist party-liner Vito Marcantonio of New York, in voting time after time against measures that are for the security of this country".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He assailed Douglas for advocating that Taiwan's seat on the United Nations Security Council be given to the People's Republic of China, as appeasement towards communism.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Late in September, Douglas complained of alleged whispering campaigns aimed at her husband's Jewish heritage, and which stated that he was a communist.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] At the end of September, the splits in the Democratic Party became open when 64 prominent Democrats, led by George Creel, endorsed Nixon and castigated Douglas.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Creel said, "She has voted consistently with Vito Marcantonio.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Belated flag-waving cannot erase this damning record, nor can the tawdry pretense of 'liberalism' excuse it." According to Creel, Downey was working behind the scenes to secure Nixon's election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] James Roosevelt's lackluster campaign led Douglas backers to state that he was not only failing to help Douglas, he was not even helping himself.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] With polls showing the two major Democratic candidates in dire straits, Roosevelt wrote to President Truman, proposing that Truman campaign in the state in the final days before the election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He also declined Douglas's pleas for a letter of support (privately calling her "one of the worst nuisances"), and even refused to allow her to be photographed with him at a signing ceremony for a water bill which would benefit California.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] When Truman flew to Wake Island in early October to confer with General Douglas MacArthur regarding the Korean situation, he returned via San Francisco, but told the press he had no political appointments scheduled.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He spoke at an event at the War Memorial Opera House during his stopover, but both Roosevelt and Douglas were relegated to orchestra-level seats, far from the presidential box.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Vice President Alben Barkley did visit the state to campaign for the Democrats.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] However, *Time* magazine wrote that he did not appear to be helpful to Douglas's campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The Vice President stated that while he was not familiar with Douglas's votes, he was certain that she had voted the way she did out of sincere conviction and urged Californians to give the Senate a "dose of brains and beauty".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Attorney General McGrath also came to California to campaign for the Democrats, and freshman Senator Hubert Humphrey of Minnesota tirelessly worked the San Joaquin Valley, talking to farmers and workers.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas adopted Boddy's "Tricky Dick" nickname for Nixon, and also referred to him as "pee wee".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Her name-calling had an effect on Nixon: when told she had called him "a young man with a dark shirt" in an allusion to Nazism, he inquired, "Did she say that?
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Why, I'll castrate her." Campaign official Bill Arnold joked that it would be difficult to do, and Nixon replied that he would do it anyway.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon returned the attacks; at friendly gatherings and especially at all-male events, he stated that Douglas was "pink right down to her underwear".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's last large-scale advertisement blitz contained another Nazi allusion.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Citing five votes in which Nixon and Marcantonio had voted together and in opposition to Douglas, it accused Nixon of using "the big lie" and stated: "HITLER invented it/STALIN perfected it/NIXON uses it".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] The iron curtain of silence has closed around the opposition camp." Through the final days of the campaign, he struck a constant drumbeat: Douglas was soft on communism.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Though polls showed Nixon well ahead, his campaign did not let up.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A fundraising solicitation warned, "Right Now Nixon Is Losing ...
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Skywriting urged voters to cast their ballots for him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Borrowing an idea from Nixon's 1946 campaign, the campaign announced that people should answer their phones, "Vote for Nixon"; random calls would be made from campaign headquarters and households that answered their phones that way would receive scarce consumer appliances.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner even instructed that 18-month-old copies of *The Saturday Evening Post*, containing a flattering story about Nixon, be left in doctor's offices, barber shops, and other places where people wait across the state.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In the last days of the campaign, Douglas finally began to receive some of the support she had hoped for.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy's paper endorsed her, while Truman praised her.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's actor husband, Melvyn Douglas, on tour with the play *Two Blind Mice* throughout the campaign, spoke out on behalf of his wife, as did movie stars Myrna Loy and Eddie Cantor.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon had several Hollywood personalities supporting him, including Howard Hughes, Cecil B.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Another actor, Ronald Reagan, was among Douglas's supporters, but when his girlfriend and future wife Nancy Davis took him to a pro-Nixon rally led by actress ZaSu Pitts, he was converted to Nixon's cause and led quiet fundraising for him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas was apparently unaware of this—30 years later she mentioned Reagan in her memoirs as someone who worked hard for her.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner had worked on Warren's 1942 campaign, but had parted ways from him, and the popular governor did not want to be connected to the Nixon campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nonetheless, Chotiner sought to maneuver him into an endorsement.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Chotiner instructed Young Republicans head and future congressman Joseph F.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Holt to follow Douglas from appearance to appearance and demand to know who she was supporting for governor, as other Young Republicans handed out copies of the Pink Sheet.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas repeatedly avoided the question, but with four days to go before the election and the Democratic candidate near exhaustion from the bitter campaign, she responded that she hoped and prayed that Roosevelt would be elected.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Despite the polls, Douglas was confident that the Democratic registration edge would lead her to victory, so much so that she offered a Roosevelt staffer a job in her senatorial office.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] On election day, November 7, 1950, Nixon defeated Douglas by 59 percent to 41.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Of California's 58 counties, Douglas won only five, all in Northern California and with relatively small populations; Nixon won every urban area.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Although Warren defeated Roosevelt by an even larger margin, Nixon won by the greatest number of votes of any 1950 Senate candidate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas, in her concession speech, declined to congratulate Nixon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Marcantonio was also defeated in his New York district.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] A week after the election, Downey announced that he was resigning for health reasons.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Warren appointed Nixon to the short remainder of Downey's term; under the Senate rules at the time, this gave Nixon seniority over the new senators sworn in during January 1951.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Nixon took office on December 4, 1950, after resigning from the House.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He used little of his seniority, since in November 1952 he was elected vice president as Dwight Eisenhower's running mate, the next step on a path that would lead him to the presidency in 1969.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Downey, who as a former senator retained floor privileges, was hired as a lobbyist by oil interests.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1952, as Republicans took over the White House and control of both houses of Congress, he was fired.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] An aide stated that the big corporations did not need Downey anymore.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Boddy, dispirited by his election defeat and feeling let down by the average citizens for whom he had sought to advocate, lapsed into semi-retirement after his primary defeat.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1952, he sold his interest in the *Daily News*, which went into bankruptcy in December 1954.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] It was rumored that Douglas would be given a political appointment in the Truman administration, but the Nixon–Douglas race had made such an appointment too controversial for the President.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] According to Democratic National Committee vice-chair India Edwards, a Douglas supporter, the former congresswoman could not have been appointed dogcatcher.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1952, she returned to acting, and eight years later campaigned for John F.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Kennedy during Nixon's first, unsuccessful presidential run.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] She also campaigned for George McGovern in his unsuccessful bid to prevent Nixon's 1972 reelection, and called for his ouster from office during the Watergate scandal.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Less than a week after the election, Douglas wrote to one of her supporters that she did not think there was anything her campaign could have done to change the result.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Blaming the war, voter mistrust of Truman's foreign policy, and high prices at home, Douglas stated that she lost in California because Nixon was able to take a large part of the women's vote and the labor vote.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Later in November, she indicated that liberals must undertake a massive effort to win in 1952.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1956, she stated in an interview that, while Nixon had never called her a communist, he had designed his whole campaign to create the impression that she was a communist or "communistic".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1959, she wrote that she had not particularly wanted to be a senator, and in 1962 she stated that the policy of her campaign was to avoid attacks on Nixon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In her memoirs, published posthumously in 1982, she wrote, "Nixon had his victory, but I had mine ...
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In 1958, Nixon, by then vice president, allegedly stated that he regretted some of the tactics his campaign had used in the campaign against Douglas, blaming his youth.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] When the statements were reported, Nixon denied them.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He issued press releases defending his campaign, and stating that any impression that Douglas was pro-communist was justified by her record.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He said Douglas was part of a whispering campaign accusing him of being "anti-Semitic and Jim Crow".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Contemporary accounts ascribed the result to a number of causes.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas friend and former Interior Secretary Harold L.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Ickes blamed Roosevelt's weak candidacy and what he believed was Nixon's use of the red scare.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Supervisor John Anson Ford of Los Angeles County chalked up the result to Nixon's skill as a speaker and a lack of objective reporting by the press.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's campaign treasurer, Alvin Meyers, stated that while labor financed Douglas's campaign, it failed to vote for her, and blamed the Truman Administration for "dumping" her.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Douglas's San Diego campaign manager claimed that 500,000 people in San Diego and Los Angeles had received anonymous phone calls alleging Douglas was a communist, though he could not name anyone who had received such a call.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] *Time* magazine wrote that Nixon triumphed "by making the Administration's failures in Asia his major issue".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] As Nixon continued his political rise and then moved towards his downfall, the 1950 race increasingly took on sinister tones.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Historian Ingrid Scobie came to a different conclusion in her biography of Douglas, *Center Stage*.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Scobie concluded that, given voter attitudes at the time, no woman could have won that race.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] In his early biography of Nixon, Mazo contrasted the two campaigns and concluded, "when compared with the surgeons of the Nixon camp, the Douglas operators performed like apprentice butchers".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Both Roger Morris and Greg Mitchell (who wrote a book about the 1950 race) conclude that Nixon spent large sums of money on the campaign, with Morris estimating $1–2 million (perhaps $12 million–$24 million today) and Mitchell suggesting twice that.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Gellman, in his later book, conceded that Nixon's officially reported amount of $4,209 was understated, but indicated that campaign finance law at that time was filled with loopholes, and few if any candidates admitted to their full spending.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] He considered Morris's and Mitchell's earlier estimates, though, to be "guess[es]" and "fantastic".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1950-united-states-senate-election-in-california] Black suggests that Nixon spent about $1.5 million and Douglas just under half of that.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The **1952 Republican National Convention** was held at the International Amphitheatre in Chicago, Illinois from July 7 to 11, 1952, and nominated Dwight D.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower of New York, nicknamed "Ike", for president and then Richard M.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The 1952 Republican convention was the first political convention to be televised live, coast-to-coast.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Experiments in regionally broadcasting conventions took place during the Republican and Democratic conventions in 1948; however, 1952 was the first year in which networks carried nationwide coverage of political conventions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Fixed cameras were placed at the back and the sides of the International Amphitheatre for the press to use collectively.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] None of these offered a straight shot of the podium on stage, so many networks supplemented their coverage with shots from their own portable cameras.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The keynote speech was delivered by MacArthur, who had become a hero to Republicans after President Truman relieved him of command in 1951 because of their disagreement about how to prosecute the Korean War, and had hopes of obtaining the presidential nomination.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In his address, MacArthur condemned the Truman administration for America's perceived loss of status on the international stage, including criticism of the Yalta Conference and the administration's handling of the war in Korea.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] MacArthur also criticized Truman on the domestic front, blaming his administration for wages that failed to keep pace with post-World War II inflation.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The speech was not well received, and did nothing to aid MacArthur's presidential campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] He curtailed his post-convention speeches and remained out of the public eye until after the election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The contest for the presidential nomination was expected to be a battle between the party's moderate-to-liberal and conservative wings.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Moderate and liberal Republicans (the "Eastern Establishment"), led by New York Governor Thomas E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Dewey, the party's unsuccessful presidential nominee in 1944 and 1948, were largely supporters of Eisenhower or Warren.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The conservative wing was led by Robert A.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Taft, who had unsuccessfully tried for the presidential nomination in 1940 and 1948.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The Taft-dominated Republican National Committee supported Taft in the dispute.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] When delegate committees met to consider the issue before the convention convened, they sustained Eisenhower's position.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Stripped of 42 delegates from the disputed states, Taft's backers realized their chances of beating Eisenhower were slim.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In his remarks during the delegate fight, Taft supporter Everett Dirksen harshly criticized Dewey and the moderate-to-liberal wing of the party, which had dominated it since 1940.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] McKeldin's nomination was seconded by Kansas Governor Edward F.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Arn, Oregon Republican Party Chairman Robert B.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Alberta Green, a delegate from West Plains, Missouri, and Hobson R.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Reynolds, an African American funeral director, state legislator from Philadelphia, and Director of the Civil Liberties Department of the Improved Benevolent and Protective Order of Elks of the World.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] After the nominations were completed, including speeches on behalf of Earl Warren, Harold Stassen, and Douglas MacArthur, the delegates proceeded to vote.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] After the first ballot, Eisenhower had 595 votes, nine short of the 604 required for the nomination, while Taft was a strong second with 500: Warren had 81, Stassen 20, and MacArthur 10.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Warren's backers refused to change their votes to Eisenhower because they still hoped for a deadlock that might enable Warren to obtain the nomination as a compromise choice.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Stassen had not received 10% of the vote, which freed his home state of Minnesota's delegates from their pledge to support him: all but one of the Stassen delegates, led by Warren E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Burger, then changed their votes to Eisenhower, giving him 614 votes and securing him the presidential nomination.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] After the revised totals were announced, Taft and Warren supporters moved to unanimously nominate Eisenhower, which the delegates did.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] As soon as Eisenhower was nominated, he visited Taft personally to request his endorsement and obtain a promise that Taft would support the Republican ticket.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Taft immediately agreed, and loyally backed Eisenhower during the general election campaign.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The nomination of Eisenhower in a single round of balloting marked the fifteenth time Republicans had selected their nominee on the first ballot.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In the twenty-five national conventions the party had held since 1856, the party had averaged four ballots to select its presidential nominees.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon's speech at a state Republican Party fundraiser in New York City on May 8, 1952, impressed Governor Thomas E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Dewey, who was an Eisenhower supporter and had formed a pro-Eisenhower delegation from New York to attend the national convention.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In a private meeting after the speech, Dewey suggested to Nixon that he would make a suitable vice presidential candidate on the ticket with Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon attended the convention as a delegate pledged to Earl Warren and represented California on the convention's platform committee.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In pre-convention remarks to reporters, Nixon touted Warren as the most prominent dark horse and suggested that if Warren was not the presidential nominee, Nixon's Senate colleague William Knowland would be a good choice for vice president.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] As the convention proceedings continued, Warren became concerned that Nixon was working for Eisenhower while ostensibly pledged to Warren.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Davis of the Hoover Institution at Stanford University, who had been a vice president at Columbia University while Eisenhower was the school's president, to tell Eisenhower that Warren resented such actions and wanted them to stop.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower informed Davis that he did not oppose Warren, because if Taft and Eisenhower deadlocked, then Warren would be his first choice for the nomination.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] In the same conversation, Eisenhower indicated that if he won the nomination, Nixon would be his first choice for the vice presidency, because Eisenhower believed the party needed to promote leaders who were aggressive, capable, and young.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower later developed a list of seven potential candidates, with Nixon's name at the top.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] After Eisenhower was nominated, his key supporters met to discuss vice presidential possibilities.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Eisenhower informed the group's chairman, Herbert Brownell Jr. that he did not wish to appear to dictate to the convention by formally sponsoring a single candidate, so the group reviewed several, including Taft, Everett Dirksen, and Alfred E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Driscoll, all of whom they quickly rejected.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Dewey then raised Nixon's name; the group quickly concurred.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Brownell checked with Eisenhower, who indicated his approval.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Brownell then called Nixon to inform him that he was Eisenhower's choice.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon accepted, then departed for Eisenhower's hotel room to discuss the details of the campaign and Eisenhower's plans for his vice president if the ticket was successful in the general election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] A group of women delegates (led by former congresswoman Clare Boothe Luce) had hopes of putting forward a female vice presidential candidate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] This group sought to nominate Senator Margaret Chase Smith of Maine, but Smith requested that her name not be used.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Noting that Eisenhower's supporters had coalesced around Nixon, Luce withdrew her nomination of Smith.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] The delegates soon assembled to formalize the selection.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Nixon asked Knowland to nominate him, and Knowland agreed.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] Bricker declined Nixon's request to second the nomination, Driscoll agreed to do so.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-national-convention] There were no other candidates, and Nixon was nominated by acclamation.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] Dewey, who was an Eisenhower supporter and had organized a pro-Eisenhower delegation from New York to attend the national convention.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] In a private meeting following the speech, Dewey suggested to Nixon that he would make a suitable vice presidential candidate to run alongside Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] Months after the convention, Eisenhower considered asking Nixon to step down as running mate due to controversy surrounding campaign expenses, but Nixon rallied public opinion with his Checkers speech and remained on the ticket.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] The Eisenhower–Nixon ticket won the 1952 election, defeating the Stevenson–Sparkman ticket, as well as the 1956 election, in which they defeated the ticket of Stevenson and Kefauver.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] Nixon was the Republican presidential nominee in 1960 but lost to John F.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-republican-party-vice-presidential-candidate-selection] He lost the election for California governor in 1962, but was elected president in 1968 and 1972.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] A presidential election was held in the United States on November 4, 1952.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican ticket of General Dwight D.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower and Senator Richard Nixon defeated the Democratic ticket of Illinois Governor Adlai Stevenson II and Senator John Sparkman in a landslide victory, becoming the first Republican president in 20 years.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election since 1928 without an incumbent president on the ballot.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson emerged victorious on the third presidential ballot of the 1952 Democratic National Convention by defeating Tennessee senator Estes Kefauver, Georgia senator Richard Russell Jr., and other candidates.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Republican nomination was primarily contested by Eisenhower, a general, widely popular for his leadership in World War II, and the conservative Ohio senator Robert A.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey and other party leaders, Eisenhower narrowly prevailed over Taft at the 1952 Republican National Convention.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He selected youthful California Senator Richard Nixon as his running mate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In the first televised presidential campaign, Eisenhower was charismatic and very well known, in sharp contrast to Stevenson.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman's handling of the Korean War and the broader Cold War, alleging Soviet spies infiltrated the U.S. government.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats faulted Eisenhower for failing to condemn Senators Joseph McCarthy, William E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Jenner, and other reactionary Republicans, who, the Democrats alleged, engaged in reckless and unwarranted attacks.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson tried to separate himself from the unpopular Truman administration.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, he campaigned on the popularity of the New Deal and stoked fears of another Great Depression under a Republican administration.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower retained his enormous popularity from the war, as was seen in his campaign slogan, "I Like Ike".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower received over 34 million votes, which at the time was the highest popular vote total a presidential candidate had received, surpassing Franklin D.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans gained among Democrats, especially urban and suburban Southerners, and White ethnic groups in the Northeast and Midwest.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The fight for the Republican nomination was between General Dwight D.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower, who became the candidate of the party's moderate Eastern Establishment; Senator Robert A.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Taft from Ohio, the longtime leader of the party's conservative wing; Governor Earl Warren of California, who appealed to Western delegates and independent voters; and former Governor Harold Stassen of Minnesota, who still had a base of support in the Midwest.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The moderate Eastern Republicans were led by New York Governor Thomas E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Dewey, the party's presidential nominee in 1944 and 1948.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The moderates tended to be interventionists who felt that the country needed to fight the Cold War overseas and confront the Soviet Union in Eurasia.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] They were also willing to accept most aspects of the social welfare state created by the New Deal in the 1930s but sought to reform the programs to be more efficient and business-friendly.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The moderates were also concerned with ending the Republicans' losing streak in presidential elections and felt that the popular Eisenhower had the best chance of beating the Democrats.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] For that reason, Dewey declined the notion of a third run for president despite his large amount of support within the party.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Republicans had been out of power for 20 years, and there was a strong sentiment that a proper two-party system needed to be re-established.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] It was also felt that the party winning the White House would have more incentive to rein in radicals and demagogues such as Wisconsin Senator Joseph McCarthy.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The conservative Republicans, led by Taft, were based in the Midwest and parts of the South.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Midwest was a bastion of conservatism and isolationist sentiment.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Dislike of Europeans, in particular the British, was common, and there was a widespread feeling that the British manipulated American foreign policy and were eager to kowtow to the Soviet Union, although such attitudes had begun to change among the younger generation who had fought in World War II.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the conservatives opposed much of the New Deal, regarding these programs as diminishing individual liberty and economic freedom.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Taft had unsuccessfully sought the Republican nomination in the 1940 and 1948 presidential elections but lost both times to moderate candidates from New York: Wilkie and Dewey respectively.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] At the age of 63, Taft felt that it was his last chance to run for president so his friends and supporters, encompassing many party regulars, worked diligently on his behalf.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] His feelings were correct, as he died about nine months after the election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Warren, although highly popular in California, refused to campaign in the presidential primaries, which limited his chances of winning the nomination.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He retained the support of the California delegation, and his supporters hoped that in the event of an Eisenhower–Taft deadlock, Warren might emerge as a compromise candidate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] After being persuaded to run, Eisenhower scored a major victory in the New Hampshire primary in which his supporters wrote his name onto the ballot and gave him an upset victory over Taft.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, until the Republican National Convention, the primaries were divided fairly evenly between the two, and when the convention opened, the race for the nomination was still too close to call.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Taft won the Nebraska, Wisconsin, Illinois, and South Dakota primaries, and Eisenhower won those in New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Massachusetts and Oregon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stassen and Warren won only their home states of Minnesota and California respectively, which effectively ended their chances of earning the nomination.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] General Douglas MacArthur also won the support of ten delegates from various states.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] When the 1952 Republican National Convention opened in Chicago, most political experts rated Taft and Eisenhower as about equal in delegate vote totals.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Lodge and Dewey proposed to evict the Taft delegates in those states and replace them with Eisenhower delegates and called the proposal "Fair Play".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Although Taft and his supporters angrily denied that charge, the convention voted to support Fair Play 658 to 548, and Taft lost many Southern delegates.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower's chances were boosted when several uncommitted state delegations, such as Michigan and Pennsylvania, decided to support him and also when Stassen released his delegates and asked them to support Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The removal of many Southern delegates and the support of the uncommitted states decided the nomination in Eisenhower's favor.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, the convention was among the most bitter and emotional in American history.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In the end, Eisenhower narrowly defeated Taft on the first ballot.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] To heal the wounds caused by the battle, he visited Taft's hotel suite and met with him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Taft issued a brief statement congratulating Eisenhower on his victory, but he was bitter about the accusation that he had stolen delegates and withheld his active support for Eisenhower for several weeks after the convention.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In September 1952, Taft and Eisenhower met again at Morningside Heights, in New York City.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower agreed to the terms, and Taft campaigned assiduously for the Republican ticket.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, Eisenhower and Taft agreed on most domestic issues, and their disagreements were primarily on foreign policy.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Though there were initial suggestions that Warren could earn the party's vice-presidential slot for the second successive election if he withdrew and endorsed Eisenhower, he ultimately chose not to do so.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower wished to award the vice-presidential nod to Stassen, who had endorsed Eisenhower and held generally similar political positions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, the party bosses wanted to find a running mate who could mollify Taft's supporters, as the schism between the moderate and conservative wings was so severe that it was feared that party's conservatives would run Taft as a third-party candidate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower had apparently given little thought to choosing his running mate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] When asked, he replied that he assumed the convention would pick someone.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The spot ultimately fell to the young California Senator Richard Nixon, who was viewed as a centrist.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Nixon was known as an aggressive campaigner and a fierce anti-communist but as one who shied away from some of the more extreme ideas of the party's right wing, including isolationism and the dismantling of the New Deal.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Most historians now believe that Eisenhower's nomination was the result of his perceived electability against the Democrats.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Most of the delegates were conservatives who would probably have supported Taft if they felt that he could win the general election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Despite not earning the presidential or the vice-presidential nomination, Warren would be appointed as Chief Justice of the United States in October 1953, and Stassen would hold various positions within Eisenhower's administration.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The expected candidate for the Democratic nomination was the incumbent President Harry S.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Since the newly passed 22nd Amendment did not apply to whoever was president at the time of its passage, he was eligible to run again.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, Truman entered 1952 with his popularity plummeting, according to polls.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Polls showed that he had a 66% disapproval rating, a record that would be matched only decades later by Richard Nixon and surpassed by George W.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman's main opponent was the populist Tennessee Senator Estes Kefauver, who had chaired a nationally televised investigation of organized crime in 1951 and was known as a crusader against crime and corruption.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Gallup poll of February 15 showed Truman's weakness.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Nationally, Truman was the choice of only 36% of Democrats, compared with 21% for Kefauver.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Among independent voters, however, Truman had only 18%, and Kefauver led with 36%.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In the New Hampshire primary, Kefauver upset Truman by winning 19,800 votes to Truman's 15,927 and capturing all eight delegates.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Kefauver graciously said that he did not consider his victory "a repudiation of Administration policies, but a desire ... for new ideas and personalities".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stung by that setback, however, Truman announced March 29 that he would not seek re-election.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman insisted in his memoirs, however, that he had decided not to run for re-election well before his defeat to Kefauver.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] With Truman's withdrawal, Kefauver became the frontrunner for the nomination, and he won most of the primaries.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Other primary winners were Senator Hubert Humphrey, who won his home state of Minnesota; Senator Richard Russell Jr. from Georgia, who won the Florida primary, and the diplomat W.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Averell Harriman, who won West Virginia.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, most states still chose their delegates to the Democratic Convention by state conventions, which meant that the party bosses, especially the mayors and governors of large Northern and Midwestern states and cities, were able to choose the Democratic nominee.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The bosses, including Truman himself, strongly disliked Kefauver since his investigations of organized crime had revealed connections between American Mafia figures and many of the big-city Democratic political organizations.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The party bosses thus viewed Kefauver as a maverick who could not be trusted and so refused to support him for the nomination.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, with Truman taking the initiative, they began to search for other more acceptable candidates.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, most of the other candidates had a major weakness.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Russell had much Southern support, but his support of racial segregation and his opposition to civil rights for black people led many liberal Northern and Midwestern delegates, pressed by their many black voters, to reject him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman favored Harriman of New York, but the latter had never held an elective office and was inexperienced in politics.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman next turned to Vice President Alben W.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Barkley but at 74, he was rejected as being too old by leaders of labor unions.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Other minor or favorite son candidates included Oklahoma Senator Robert S.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Dever, Minnesota Senator Hubert Humphrey, and Arkansas Senator J.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] One candidate soon emerged who seemingly had few political weaknesses, Governor Adlai Stevenson of Illinois.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The grandson of former Vice President Adlai E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson, he came from a distinguished family in Illinois and was well known as a gifted orator, intellectual, and political moderate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In the spring of 1952, Truman attempted to convince Stevenson to take the presidential nomination, but Stevenson said that he wanted to run for re-election as Governor of Illinois.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] However, Stevenson never completely took himself out of the race, and as the convention approached, many party bosses and normally apolitical citizens hoped that he could be "drafted" to run.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The 1952 Democratic National Convention was held in Chicago in the same Coliseum that the Republicans had gathered in several weeks earlier.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Since the convention was being held in his home state, Governor Stevenson, who still proclaimed that he was not a presidential candidate, was asked to give the welcoming address to the delegates.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He proceeded to give a witty and stirring address that led his supporters to begin a renewed round of efforts to nominate him despite his protests.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] After meeting with Jacob Arvey, the boss of the Illinois delegation, Stevenson finally agreed to enter his name as a candidate for the nomination.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The party bosses from other large Northern and Midwestern states quickly joined in support.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Kefauver led on the first ballot, but he had far fewer votes than necessary to win.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson gradually gained strength until he was nominated on the third ballot.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] After the delegates nominated Stevenson, the convention then turned to selecting a vice-presidential nominee.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] After narrowing it down to Senators John Sparkman, and A.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Mike Monroney, President Truman and a small group of political insiders chose Sparkman, a conservative segregationist from Alabama, for the nomination.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The convention largely complied and nominated Sparkman as Stevenson's running mate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He was chosen because of his Southern identity and conservative record, which party leaders hoped would create a balanced ticket.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Sparkman remained in the Senate until his retirement in 1979.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Eisenhower campaign was one of the first presidential campaigns to make a major and concerted effort to win the female vote.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Many of his radio and television commercials discussed topics such as education, inflation, ending the Korean War, and other issues that were thought to appeal to women.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Eisenhower campaign made extensive use of female campaign workers, who made phone calls to likely Eisenhower voters, distributed "Ike" buttons and leaflets, and threw parties to build support for the Republican ticket in their neighborhoods.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] On election day, Eisenhower won a solid majority of the female vote.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower campaigned by attacking "Korea, Communism, and Corruption", issues that the Republicans regarded as the failures of the outgoing Truman administration to solve.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Eisenhower campaign accused the administration of "neglecting Latin America" and thus "leading them into the arms of wily Communist agents waiting to exploit local misery and capitalize on any opening to communize the Americas".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Charges that Soviet spies had infiltrated the government plagued the Truman administration and became a "major campaign issue" for Eisenhower.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The Republicans blamed the Democrats for the military's failure to be fully prepared to fight in Korea, accused the Democrats of harboring communist spies within the federal government, and criticized the Truman administration for the many officials who had been accused of various crimes.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson hoped to exploit the rift between the conservative Taft Republicans and the moderate Eisenhower Republicans.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In a speech in Baltimore, Stevenson said, "The GOP elephant has two heads nowadays, and I can't tell from day to day who's driving the poor beast, Senator Taft or the General.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] I doubt that America will entrust its future, its hopes, to the master of a house divided against itself." Stevenson, Truman, and other Democrats campaigning that fall also criticized Senators Joseph McCarthy, William E.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Jenner, and other right-wing Republicans for what they believed were reckless and unwarranted attacks and congressional investigations into leading government officials and public servants.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In a Salt Lake City speech Stevenson stated that right-wing Republicans were "quick with accusations, with defamatory hints and whispering campaigns when they see a chance to scare or silence those with whom they disagree.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Rudely, carelessly, they invade the field of thought, of conscience, which belongs to God, and not to Senators. ...
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman repeatedly criticized Senator McCarthy's character and temperament and called on Eisenhower to repudiate him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson ridiculed right-wing Republicans "who hunt Communists in the Bureau of Wildlife and Fisheries while hesitating to aid the gallant men and women who are resisting the real thing in the front lines of Europe and Asia. ...
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] They are finally the men who seemingly believe that we can confound the Kremlin by frightening ourselves to death." In return, McCarthy often jokingly confused the names Adlai and Alger, the first name of the convicted Soviet spy Alger Hiss, by stating "Alger, I mean Adlai" in his speeches.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] McCarthy exploited the fact that Stevenson had defended Hiss as innocent despite all of the evidence otherwise.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] McCarthy, in response to Stevenson's criticisms, also stated during the campaign that he would like to get on the Stevenson campaign trail "with a club and make a good and loyal American" out of Stevenson.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Neither Stevenson nor Sparkman had been a part of the Truman administration, and both largely ignored its record, preferred to hark back to the Roosevelt's New Deal achievements, and warned against a repetition of the Great Depression under President Herbert Hoover if Eisenhower was elected.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower's goal to unite the Republican Party for the fall campaign led him to campaign with and endorse several Republicans with whom he was uncomfortable.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Truman, who had once been friends with Eisenhower, never forgot what he saw as a betrayal.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower retained his enormous personal popularity from his leading role in World War II, and huge crowds turned out to see him around the nation.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] His campaign slogan, "I Like Ike", was one of the most popular in American history.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson attracted the support of the young emerging postwar intellectual class, but Eisenhower was seen as more appealing to Main Street.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson was ridiculed in some quarters as too effeminate to be president, which was sometimes used as a euphemism for a male homosexual.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The staunchly-conservative *New York Daily News* called him "Adelaide" Stevenson even though he had a reputation as a ladies' man, divorced in 1949, and remained single throughout 1952.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] A notable event of the 1952 campaign concerned a scandal that emerged when Richard Nixon, Eisenhower's running mate, was accused by several newspapers of receiving $18,000 in undeclared "gifts" from wealthy donors.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In reality, contributions were by design only from early supporters and limited to $1,000, with full accountability.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Nixon, who had been accusing the Democrats of hiding corruption, suddenly found himself on the defensive.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower and his aides even considered dropping Nixon from the ticket and picking Senator William Knowland as a replacement running mate.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower, who barely knew Nixon, waffled and refused to comment on the incident.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Nixon saved his political career, however, with a dramatic half-hour speech, the "Checkers speech", on live television.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In this speech, Nixon denied the charges against him, gave a detailed account of his modest financial assets, and offered a glowing assessment of Eisenhower's candidacy.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The highlight of the speech came when Nixon stated that a supporter had given his daughters a gift, a dog named Checkers, and that he would not return it because his daughters loved it.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The "Checkers speech" led hundreds of thousands of citizens nationwide to wire the Republican National Committee to urge the Republican Party to keep Nixon on the ticket, and Eisenhower stayed with him.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the red-baiting of the Republicans' right wing, the campaign on the whole was conducted with a considerable degree of dignity, and Stevenson was seen as reinvigorating a Democratic Party that had become exhausted after 20 years in power and as refreshing its appeal with younger voters.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He accused Eisenhower of silently tolerating McCarthy's excesses.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson went before the American Legion, a bastion of hardline conservatism, and boldly declared that there was nothing patriotic or American about what McCarthy was doing.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Even with the dignified nature of the campaign, the dislike between the two candidates was visible.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson criticized Eisenhower's noncondemnation of McCarthy and his use of television spots, and Eisenhower, who had initially respected Stevenson, came in time to view him as simply another career politician, which he strongly disliked.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The 1952 election campaign was the first one to make use of the new medium of television, partly by the efforts of Rosser Reeves, the head of Ted Bates, Inc., a leading advertising firm.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves had initially proposed a series of radio spots to Dewey in the 1948 campaign, but Dewey considered them undignified.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves later maintained that Dewey might have won the election if he had been slightly more open-minded.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Studying Douglas MacArthur's keynote speech at the Republican Convention in July, Reeves believed that the general's words were "powerful" but "unfocused" and "all over the map".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower's public speeches were even worse since he was unable to make his point to the voting public in a clear intelligible manner.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves felt that Eisenhower needed to condense his message down to a few simple easily-digestible slogans.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower at first also fared poorly on television and had a difficult time appearing relaxed and at ease on camera.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The television lighting was not flattering and made him look old and unattractive.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] In particular, his forehead tended to glisten under the lights.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower became upset when the CBS correspondent Dave Schoenbrun pointed that out and suggested him to try to alter his poses to make his forehead less noticeable and to apply makeup so that it would not shine from the lighting.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eventually, he gave in and agreed to those modifications.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves also wanted Eisenhower to not wear his eyeglasses on camera to look younger, but since he could not read the prompter board without them, Reeves devised a large handwritten signboard.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Reeves's television work, although pioneering, was the subject of considerable criticism on the grounds that he was attempting to sell a presidential candidate to the public in the same manner that one might sell a car or a brand of toothpaste.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He made a point of the fact that he did not watch or even own a television, and the same went for many members of his inner circle.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Both campaigns made use of television ads.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] A notable ad for Eisenhower was an issue-free feel-good animated cartoon with a soundtrack song by Irving Berlin called "I Like Ike".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] For the first time, a presidential candidate's personal medical history was released publicly, as were partial versions of his financial histories, because of the issues that had been raised in Nixon's speech.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Near the end of the campaign, Eisenhower, in a major speech, announced that if he won the election he would go to Korea to see if he could end the war.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] His great military prestige, combined with the public's weariness with the conflict, gave Eisenhower the final boost he needed to win.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Throughout the entire campaign, Eisenhower led in all opinion polls and by wide margins in most of them.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] To circumvent the local Republican Party organizations, which were mostly controlled by Taft supporters, the Eisenhower forces created a nationwide network of grassroots clubs, "Citizens for Eisenhower".
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Independents and Democrats were welcome, as the group specialized in canvassing neighborhoods and holding small-group meetings.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Citizens for Eisenhower hoped to revitalize the party by expanding its activist ranks and by supporting moderate and internationalist policies.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] It did not endorse candidates other than Eisenhower, but he paid it little attention after he had won, and it failed to maintain its impressive starting momentum.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, it energized the conservative Republicans, which led finally to the Barry Goldwater campaign of 1964.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Longtime Republican activists viewed the newcomers with suspicion and hostility.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] More significantly, activism in support of Eisenhower did not translate into enthusiasm for the party's cause.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] On election day, Eisenhower won a decisive victory by winning over 55% of the popular vote and carrying 39 of the 48 states.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson did not win a single state north of the Mason–Dixon line or west of Arkansas; he did succeed in winning back the four states which Strom Thurmond had won at the previous election, but lost all but five of the states that Truman had won that year.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower took three Southern states that the Republicans had won only once since Reconstruction: Virginia, Florida, and Texas.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He also carried Tennessee, a state that only voted for Republicans twice after Reconstruction.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] It was the last time the Republicans won Missouri until 1968 and the last time that a Republican won the election without Kentucky.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Stevenson's 700-vote win was the smallest percentage margin in any state since Woodrow Wilson had won New Hampshire by 56 votes in 1916.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 3,099 counties/independent cities making returns, Eisenhower won the most popular votes in 2,104 (67.89%) while Stevenson carried 995 (32.11%).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] Eisenhower won in 21 of the 39 cities with a population above 250,000.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] He won in six of the eight largest Southern cities.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/1952-united-states-presidential-election] The election was the first in which a computer, the UNIVAC I (and Monrobot III), was used to predict the results; it came within 3.5% of Eisenhower's popular vote tally and four votes of his electoral vote total.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The **Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act** (**ANCSA**) was signed into law by President Richard Nixon on December 18, 1971, constituting what is still the largest land claims settlement in United States history.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] ANCSA was intended to resolve long-standing issues surrounding aboriginal land claims in Alaska, as well as to stimulate economic development throughout Alaska.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The settlement established Alaska Native claims to the land by transferring titles to twelve Alaska Native regional corporations and over 200 local village corporations.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] A thirteenth regional corporation was later created for Alaska Natives who no longer resided in Alaska.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The act is codified in chapter 33 of title 43 of the US Code.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] When Alaska became a state in 1959, section 4 of the Alaska Statehood Act provided that any existing Alaska Native land claims would be unaffected by statehood and held in status quo.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Yet while section 4 of the act preserved Native land claims until later settlement, section 6 allowed for the state government to claim lands deemed vacant.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Section 6 granted the state of Alaska the right to select lands then in the hands of the federal government, with the exception of Native territory.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] As a result, nearly 104.5 million acres (423,000 km2) from the public domain would eventually be transferred to the state.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The state government also attempted to acquire lands under section 6 of the Statehood Act that were subject to Native claims under section 4, and that were currently occupied and used by Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The federal Bureau of Land Management began to process the Alaska government's selections without taking into account the Native claims and without informing the affected Native groups.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] It was against this backdrop that the original language for a land claims settlement was developed.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] A 9.2-magnitude earthquake struck the state in 1964.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Recovery efforts drew the attention of the federal government.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The Federal Field Committee for Development Planning in Alaska decided that Natives should receive $100 million and 10% of revenue as a royalty.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Nothing was done with this proposal, however, and a freeze on land transfers remained in effect.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In 1966, Emil Notti called for a statewide meeting inviting numerous leaders around Alaska to gather and create the first meeting of a committee.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The historic meeting was held October 18, 1966 - on the 99th anniversary of the transfer of Alaska from Russia.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Notti presided over the three-day conference as it discussed matters of land recommendations, claims committees, and political challenges the act would have in getting through congress.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Many respected politicians and businessmen attended the meeting and delegates were astonished at the attention which they received from well-known political figures of the state.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The growing presence and political importance of Natives was evidenced when members were able to gain election to seven of the sixty seats in the legislature.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] When the group met a second time early in 1967, it emerged with a new name, The Alaska Federation of Natives (AFN), and a new full-time President, Emil Notti.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] AFN went on to profoundly change the human rights and economic stability of the Alaska Native population.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In 1967, Governor Walter Hickel summoned a group of Indigenous leaders and politicians to work out a settlement that would be satisfactory to Natives.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The group met for ten days and asked for $20 million in exchange for requested lands.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] They proposed receiving 10% of federal mineral lease revenue for ten years, once the freeze which had been placed on land patents to allow oil exploration was lifted.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In 1968, the Atlantic-Richfield Company discovered oil at Prudhoe Bay on the Arctic coast, catapulting the issue of land ownership into headlines.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In order to lessen the difficulty of drilling at such a remote location and transporting the oil to the lower 48 states, the oil companies proposed building a pipeline to carry the oil across Alaska to the port of Valdez.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] At Valdez, the oil would be loaded onto tankers and shipped to the contiguous states.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The plan had been approved, but a permit to construct the pipeline, which would cross lands involved in the land claims dispute, could not be granted until the Native claims were settled.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Hearings were held for the first time before the United States House's Subcommittee on Indian Affairs in July 1968.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Among those who attended the hearings were officials and legislators, as well as Laura Bergt, Roger Connor, Thoda Forslund, Cliff Groh, Barry Jackson, Flore Lekanof, Notti, and Morris Thompson.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In 1969, President Nixon appointed Hickel as Secretary of the Interior.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The Alaska Federation of Natives (AFN) protested against Hickel's nomination, but he was eventually confirmed.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] He worked with the AFN, negotiating with Native leaders and state government over the disputed lands.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Offers went back and forth, with each rejecting the other's proposals.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The AFN wanted rights to land, while then-Governor Keith Miller believed Natives did not have legitimate claims to state land in light of the provisions of the Alaska Statehood Act.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] On July 8, 1970, Nixon delivered a speech reversing the Indian termination policy in favor of allowing tribal self-determination.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The following month, he established the National Council on Indian Opportunity, headed by Vice President Spiro Agnew, which included eight Native leaders: Frank Belvin (Choctaw), Bergt (Iñupiat), Betty Mae Jumper (Seminole), Earl Old Person (Blackfeet), John C.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] (Seneca), Harold Shunk (Yankton-Sioux), and Joseph C.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] During the state administration of Governor William A.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Egan positions were staked out upon which the AFN and other stakeholders could largely agree.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Native leaders, in addition to Alaska's congressional delegation and the state's newly elected Governor Egan, eventually reached the basis for presenting an agreement to Congress.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] That meeting held on March 12, marked a turning-point in negotiations with the various parties.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The proposed settlement terms faced challenges in both houses but found a strong ally in Senator Henry M.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The most controversial issues that continued to hold up approval were methods for determining land selection by Alaska Natives and financial distribution.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] With major petroleum dollars on the line, pressure mounted to achieve a definitive legislative resolution at the federal level.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In 1971, the Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act was signed into law by President Nixon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] It abrogated Native claims to aboriginal lands except those that are the subject of the law.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In return, Natives retained up to 44 million acres (180,000 km2) of land and were paid $963 million.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The land and money were to be divided among regional, urban, and village tribal corporations established under the law, often recognizing existing leadership.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Alaskan officials were originally divided on the bill, though by 1970, with Interior Secretary Wally Hickel, Governor William A.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Egan, Representative Nick Begich Sr. and Senators Ted Stevens and Mike Gravel all backing the bill, the opposition died down.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Stevens was particularly strongminded, and was key in the bill's passage.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In 1971, barely one million acres of land in Alaska were in private hands.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] ANCSA, together with section 6 of Alaska Statehood Act, which the new act allowed to come to fruition, affected ownership to about 148.5 million acres (601,000 km2) of land in Alaska once wholly controlled by the federal government.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] That is larger by 6 million acres (24,000 km2) than the combined areas of Maine, Vermont, New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, Connecticut, New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland and Virginia.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] When the bill passed in 1971, it included provisions that had never before been attempted in previous United States settlements with Native Americans.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The newly passed Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act created twelve Native regional economic development corporations.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Each corporation was associated with a specific region of Alaska and the Natives who had traditionally lived there.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] This innovative approach to native settlements engaged the tribes in corporate capitalism.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The idea originated with the AFN, who believed that the Natives would have to become a part of the capitalist system in order to survive.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] As stockholders in these corporations, the Natives could earn some income and stay in their traditional villages.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] If the corporations were managed properly, they could make profits that would enable individuals to stay, rather than having to leave Native villages to find better work.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] This was intended to help preserve Native culture.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Alaska Natives had three years from passage of ANCSA to make land selections of the 44 million acres (180,000 km2) granted under the act.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In some cases Native corporations received outside aid in surveying the land.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] For instance, Doyon, Limited (one of the 13 regional corporations) was helped by the Geophysical Institute of the University of Alaska.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The Institute determined which land contained resources such as minerals and coal.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] NASA similarly provided satellite imagery to aid in Native corporations finding areas most suited for vegetation and their traditional subsistence culture.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The imagery showed locations of caribou and moose, as well as forests with marketable timber.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] In total about 7 million acres (28,000 km2) were analyzed for Doyon.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Natives were able to choose tens of thousands of acres of land rich with timber while Doyon used mineral analysis to attract businesses.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The state of Alaska to date has been granted approximately 85% or 90 million acres (360,000 km2) of the land claims it has made under ANCSA.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The state is entitled to a total of 104.5 million acres (423,000 km2) under the terms of the Statehood Act.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Originally the state had 25 years after passage of the Alaska Statehood Act to file claims under section 6 of the act with the Bureau of Land Management (BLM).
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Amendments to ANCSA extended that deadline until 1994, with the expectation that BLM would complete processing of land transfers subject to overlapping Native claims by 2009.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Nonetheless, some Native and state selections under ANCSA remained unresolved as late as December 2014.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] There was largely positive reaction to ANCSA, although not entirely.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The act was supported by Natives as well as non-Natives, and likewise enjoyed bipartisan support.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Natives were heavily involved in the legislative process, and the final draft of the act used many AFN ideas.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Some Natives have argued that ANCSA has hastened cultural genocide of Alaska Natives.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Some Natives critiqued ANCSA as an illegitimate treaty since only tribal leaders were involved and the provisions of the act were not voted on by indigenous populations.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] One native described it as a social and political experiment.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Critics have also argued that Natives so feared massacre or incarceration that they offered no resistance to the act.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Others have argued that the settlement was arguably the most generous afforded by the United States to a Native group.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] They note that some of the largest and most profitable corporations in the state are the twelve created by ANCSA.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Other critics attacked the act as "Native welfare" and such complaints continue to be expressed.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The corporation system has been critiqued, as in some cases stockholders have sold land to outside corporations that have leveled forests and extracted minerals.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] But supporters of the system argue that it has provided economic benefits for indigenous peoples that outweigh these problems.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] Additionally, most regions and some villages have created their own nonprofits providing social services and health care through grant funding and federal compacts.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] The objectives of these nonprofits are varied, but focus generally on cultural and educational activities.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] These include scholarships for Native students, sponsorship of cultural and artistic events, preservation efforts for Native languages, and protection of sites with historic or religious importance.
[src:alaska-native-claims-settlement-act/alaska-native-claims-settlement-act] ANCSA created about 224 village and urban corporations.
